window.ROOT_RULES = {"system":{"name":"Root: The Roleplaying Game","publisher":"Magpie Games (2021)","engine":"Powered by the Apocalypse","roll":"2d6 + stat","tiers":{"10+":"strong hit","7-9":"weak hit","6-":"miss"},"moveRoll":{"10+":"Strong hit: you get what you want, on the best terms.","7-9":"Weak hit: you get what you want, but with a cost, complication, or lesser degree.","6-":"Miss: the GM makes a move; things go wrong (you usually still mark experience)."}},"stats":["Charm","Cunning","Finesse","Luck","Might"],"statDescriptions":{"Charm":"social grace, presence, likeability.","Cunning":"craftiness, quick thinking, deception.","Finesse":"manual dexterity, precision, stealth, marksmanship.","Luck":"fortune, providence, the favor of fate.","Might":"physical strength, toughness, force."},"statSoftRange":{"min":-1,"max":3,"hard":false},"harmTracks":[{"name":"Injury","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. A harm track can be raised to a maximum of 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents toughness. (The Arbiter move 'Hardy' grants +1 injury box.)"},{"name":"Exhaustion","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. Cleared by following your Nature. Max 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents reserves of energy. (The Harrier move 'Cross Country' grants +1 exhaustion box.)"},{"name":"Depletion","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. Max 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents carried supplies / 'pockets'. (The Tinker move 'Big Pockets' grants +2 depletion boxes.)"}],"economy":{"Value":"Abstract wealth/barter (MIN 0). Playbooks set a Starting Value (see each playbook's extras.startingValue).","Load":"How much depletion-worthy gear is carried (MIN 0)."},"factions":[{"name":"The Eyrie Dynasties","description":"The old regents of the Woodland, led by one royal monarch or another alongside a court of viziers. Rigid, tradition-bound, arrogant, and ambitious.\n\nThe Eyrie Dynasties ruled the Woodland for years and years, but those times were far from peaceful. The Eyrie helped structure the Woodland into a larger entity, but they were just as likely to tear the Woodland apart as a new group of royals tried to seize power from the old group. They lost power because of just such a conflict, creating the opportunity for the Marquisate to invade. Now they’re struggling to regain the territory they see as rightfully theirs.\n\nThe Eyrie won’t be content until they have reestablished firm control over the Woodland, quelling any rebellions and pushing back any outsiders. They seek a return to the way things were."},{"name":"The Marquisate","description":"The invaders from another empire, led by the Marquise de Cat. Industrializing, forceful, opportunistic, and pragmatic.\n\nThe Marquisate is, at heart, a foreign power come from far-off Le Monde de Cat to conquer the Woodland. But it grows more tied to the Woodland each day. It builds new structures across controlled clearings; it recruits new soldiers and agents directly from ruled denizens; and it forces the culture of the Marquisate upon the Woodland, even as the Marquisate itself changes to adapt.\n\nThe core goal of the Marquisate remains what it has always been—to control the Woodland as another holding of Le Monde, a base from which the Marquise can further her ambitions. But as it adds new members to its ranks, its goals are drawn towards establishing order, industry, and prosperity in the Woodland."},{"name":"The Woodland Alliance","description":"The vehement, vocal rebels of the Woodland. Passionate, disorganized, outmatched, and zealous.\n\nThe Woodland Alliance is a new, rising power in the Woodland. There have been rebellions before, of course, but rarely have the denizens of the Woodland been able to organize revolt across multiple clearings. The Alliance’s ability to wage war across the Woodland gives them a real chance to change the nature of rulership in the Woodland.\n\nThe Woodland Alliance is determined to overcome the other factions that seek to dominate the Woodland. Ostensibly, their members also seek new government after the revolution…but their leaders only truly agree on overthrowing the old powers, not on what the new government looks like. The leaders of the Woodland Alliance also show differing levels of willingness to sacrifice the denizens themselves for the sake of the larger Woodland."},{"name":"The Denizens","description":"The average inhabitants of the Woodland. Conservative, timid, downtrodden, and standoffish.\n\nThe denizens aren’t a faction, as such—they don’t have a dominant organizing principle, besides being “civilians.” They’re the individuals throughout the Woodland who aren’t devoted to any particular faction. They’re connected by trade and by travelers’ stories.\n\nThe denizens, above all else, just want to live and be safe. There may be outliers looking to pick fights, but when denizens want to fight for causes, they veer towards membership in one of the factions. What defines the denizens is their dominant interest in continued survival amid the more powerful factions and their concern with the “ordinary” problems that arise in their day-to-day lives."},{"name":"The Vagabonds","description":"Miscreants, outcasts, and strangers. Rebels, mercenaries, and vigilantes. Vagabonds have always been a part of the Woodland. Those who weren’t safe enough, accepted enough, or satisfied enough to settle down in a clearing. Those who didn’t, couldn’t, or wouldn’t commit themselves to any particular faction. Those who were capable, skilled, and morally flexible.\n\n“Vagabond” is an all-encompassing term for this kind of denizen, an individual who moves around from clearing to clearing, taking on odd, dangerous jobs, and likely causing trouble wherever they go. A vagabond is usually highly skilled compared to the average denizen—you don’t survive for long in the lifestyle unless you’re skilled or protected by another skilled vagabond. And they usually have a certain moral flexibility, a willingness to perform jobs for different, opposing factions, or to perform jobs that other denizens might find distasteful.\n\nIn particular, there is one act that sets all vagabonds apart from the rest of the Woodland: vagabonds are willing to travel through the forests. More impressive still, vagabonds are capable of accomplishing this feat with a fair chance of surviving. Most other denizens know better; they stick to the paths or clearings, the safe spaces, the places where authorities and guards are around to deal with bandits or bears or other threats. But the vagabonds, they’ll cut through deep, thick forests, potentially traveling faster than any path-bound force. If the pay is right, they’ll gladly troop into forests to root out bandits, or find their way to ancient ruins in search of relics and treasure.\n\nThe capabilities of vagabonds are the source of their value. The Marquisate, the Eyrie Dynasties, and the Woodland Alliance all have plenty of work for vagabonds to take on. A vagabond is most likely a match for any one soldier from any faction, and many vagabonds are capable of contending with entire squads. Vagabond tinkers can create devices and equipment that no normal\n\nsmith would even conceive of; vagabond vagrants can infiltrate dangerous spaces with lies and tricks no other denizen would be brave (or mad) enough to try; vagabond rangers can move a band through forests with a speed no other force can match. Vagabonds may be dire troublemakers, but they’re so useful that most factions have a base level of tolerance for the problems they create.\n\nVagabonds don’t tend to travel in groups. They’re inherently loners, driven by their own quirks or desires to be apart from the rest of Woodland society. They’ll often meet one another through their travels, however, coming to know each other’s names and natures. They might even work together, when the job is tough and the reward is enough.\n\nIf a band of vagabonds were to arise, capable of sticking together, willing to help each other out and overcome challenges collectively…they could be a force to respect and fear. There are stories of such vagabond bands in the Woodland’s myths, though it’s hard to determine if any such tales are more than fable. But the alleged deeds of prior vagabond bands range from rescuing princes to defeating tyrants and freeing subjugated denizens.\n\nA whole band of vagabonds, shoring up each other’s weaknesses and supporting each other’s strengths, has the potential to tip the scale on the larger conflict between the factions…"}],"reputation":{"scale":[{"status":3,"label":"Legendary","effect":"a hero of the faction; positive stories, some true, are told."},{"status":2,"label":"Esteemed","effect":"an honored figure whose deeds are recognized."},{"status":1,"label":"Respected","effect":"treated with politeness and valued."},{"status":0,"label":"Unknown or Ambivalent","effect":"no clear, consistent view of you."},{"status":-1,"label":"Disdained","effect":"disliked, treated with mild contempt."},{"status":-2,"label":"Reviled","effect":"deeply scorned, two steps from a real enemy."},{"status":-3,"label":"Feared or Hated","effect":"a foe of the faction, met with deep fear and hatred."}],"statusBounds":{"min":-3,"max":3,"hard":true},"tracking":"Each Faction Reputation tracks a Status (hard -3..+3) plus checked Prestige Marked / Notoriety Marked boxes accumulating toward the next step. Filling prestige boxes to the next threshold raises status; filling notoriety boxes lowers it."},"natures":[{"name":"Arsonist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you use needlessly destructive or damaging methods to solve a problem."},{"name":"Combative","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to start a fight against overwhelming opposition."},{"name":"Competitive","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take dramatically unnecessary risks to show off."},{"name":"Cynic","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly and directly ask dangerous questions about an accepted \"truth\"."},{"name":"Defender","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put yourself in harm's way to defend someone against injustice or dire threat."},{"name":"Dutiful","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take on a dangerous or difficult task on behalf of another."},{"name":"Extrovert","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you share a moment of real warmth, friendship, or enjoyment with someone."},{"name":"Glutton","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you overindulge on vices like drink, food, and gambling."},{"name":"Hustler","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to spring a con on a powerful or dangerous mark."},{"name":"Kleptomaniac","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to selfishly steal something valuable or important."},{"name":"Loner","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation alone, without backup or assistance."},{"name":"Peacemaker","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you resolve a dangerous conflict nonviolently."},{"name":"Perfectionist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you replace someone else’s existing tool or resource with something truly great."},{"name":"Pilgrim","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you find an expert in a skill you don't possess."},{"name":"Punisher","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you tell a powerful or dangerous villain to their face that you will punish them."},{"name":"Radical","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you espouse dangerous ideas to the wrong audience."},{"name":"Rebellious","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you grievously insult, defy, or anger figures of authority."},{"name":"Survivor","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to flee or cover allies' flight from a dangerous or overwhelming situation."},{"name":"Braggart","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you confidently and publicly accept an excessively perilous challenge."},{"name":"Commander","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you assert authority over a group of non-vagabonds in a tense situation."},{"name":"Cowardly","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you willingly surrender to hostile forces."},{"name":"Curious","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter danger to investigate an interesting situation or location further."},{"name":"Generous","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you provide meaningful quantities of supplies to those in need."},{"name":"Gossip","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you reveal new and important information to someone who can act on it."},{"name":"Improviser","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you attempt to solve a technical problem without appropriate tools or skills."},{"name":"Inspiring","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take action that clears the morale track of an NPC or group of NPCs."},{"name":"Martyr","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you engage overwhelming odds to protect others."},{"name":"Muckraker","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter somewhere off-limits to discover incriminating secrets."},{"name":"Populist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly try to rally a group of denizens to take action against injustice."},{"name":"Vain","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you make a big show of intervening in a situation that doesn’t involve you to help or protect someone."},{"name":"Activist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly confront the leadership of a clearing about changes you think are vital to the community's success."},{"name":"Advocate","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you confront a powerful NPC about their mistreatment of the powerless or weak."},{"name":"Agent","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you convince someone influential to allow you to represent their interests."},{"name":"Avenger","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly attack those who have wronged you or your sworn vassals and wards."},{"name":"Bandit","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to use the threat of force to secure valuables from formidable opposition."},{"name":"Believer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly call out a symbol or authority dedicated to beliefs opposed to yours."},{"name":"Companion","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you effusively praise a friend to a powerful person or group."},{"name":"Exemplar","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly take on a challenging task on behalf of the Just and those they represent."},{"name":"Explorer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a ruin or other dangerous area of the forest."},{"name":"Healer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you attempt to start a dialogue between two foes from different factions."},{"name":"Hero","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you outright attack a dangerous, oppressive, or villainous NPC."},{"name":"Historian","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you refuse to allow someone to cover up or obscure the truth."},{"name":"Legend","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put on a performace in front of a large, attentive audience."},{"name":"Merchant","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you carry valuable goods or treasure past danger, difficulty, or blockade."},{"name":"Observer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation to try to witness a significant or secret event or meet an important individual."},{"name":"Rogue","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you attempt to doublecross, triplecross, or betray a powerful or dangerous NPC."},{"name":"Schemer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you promise valuable resources to a dangerous Woodland figure to secure their aid."},{"name":"Scion","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter danger to attack the enemies or defend the allies of your parents."},{"name":"Sworn","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly commit to resolve a dangerous conflict on behalf of someone vulnerable."},{"name":"Trailblazer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you depart on a wild and risky new course of action with others."}],"drives":[{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction.","description":"Your Reputation is the number, not simply prestige boxes. The actual value of your Reputation has to go up. You advance for any time your Reputation with any faction goes up (although again, only once per session). Whether your Reputation moves from –3 to –2 or +2 to +3, it still counts."},{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order.","description":"“Topple” means that the figure or order has been deposed, removed from power, at least temporarily (it doesn’t always have to be permanent). Who or what qualifies as a “dangerously overbearing figure or order” is a matter of discussion between players and GM, with the GM having the final call."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence.","description":"An “illicit, criminal goal” should be a goal that any force of law and order in the area would frown upon. “A believable veneer of innocence” means that, by and large, most denizens aware of the crime have no reason to blame you. Maybe they are suspicious of you, but they definitely don’t have evidence."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds.","description":"“Illicitly score a significant prize” or “pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds” offer two ways to advance with this drive. “A significant prize” can be relative to the vagabonds’ circumstances, but it should always be something either of extraordinary monetary value or of extraordinary intrinsic value—an incredibly valuable gemstone, or the gemstone that determines the next ruler of the Eyrie, respectively. “Pulling off” the caper in no way means that everything went well; all it means is that you more or less achieved your desired end. When determining whether “impressive odds” applies, think about whether or not it makes a good story; you wouldn’t recount the tale of duping some guard, but you would absolutely recount the tale of robbing the local governor’s mansion."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests.","description":"Both the “new wonder” and the “ruin” are understood to be “in the forests”— this drive is for vagabonds interested in exploring the forests. A new ruin is one you haven’t been to before, not necessarily one that no one has found before. A new wonder is anything impressive, surprising, exciting, or special that you find in the forests—think of it as something you could tell other denizens about and have them listen with rapt attention."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression.","description":"“Free a group of denizens” doesn’t mean “permanently free,” but it does mean that for the moment, their bonds are removed. “Oppression” can take many different shapes, but it must be real; the oppressed denizens must themselves believe fully in their own oppression."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure.","description":"“A serious payday or treasure” can be from anywhere, but it has to be worth a LOT of money. The amount can be relative—a “serious payday” for a dirt-poor vagabond might be less than for a rich vagabond—but should be approximately 5-Value or more."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction.","description":"Your Reputation is the number, not simply notoriety boxes. The actual value of your Reputation has to go down. You advance for any time a Reputation with any faction goes down (although again, only once per session). Whether the Reputation moves from +3 to +2 or –2 to –3, it still counts."},{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual.","description":"“Justice” is highly dependent upon the exact situation and should be discussed between the GM and the players. If need be, the GM has final say. “Wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual” means that the victim was genuinely harmed, and the perpetrator is of greater power, whether de facto or de jure."},{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself.","description":"You can name any character, including an NPC you make up from scratch or another PC if you so choose. If you name an NPC, make sure you consider how you get orders from them—if they stay put and you travel, then you can still receive orders from them through missives. “At a great cost to yourself” means that you undertake great risk or suffer great consequence in carrying out their orders. If you carry out their orders while suffering nothing, risking nothing, and paying no cost, then you haven’t satisfied the drive."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies.","description":"“Your moral principles” have to be real—no “but my moral principles say it’s fine to steal from anyone at any time!” By choosing this drive, you are saying your character has real moral principles, a code of conduct that matters to them. You don’t have to outline every aspect of their principles, but at character creation you should have a notion of some overriding principle that matters to your\n\ncharacter—“Violence is never justified,” “The poor deserve as much succor as we can give,” “Democracy is the only fair mode of government.” “Express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies” means that your principles dictated your action, and because of those actions you and your friends paid a meaningful price."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe.","description":"You can name any character, including an NPC you make up from scratch or another PC if you so choose. If you name an NPC, then you should either plan on their traveling with you, or you should understand that you are unlikely to advance with this drive unless time passes or you are specifically in their home clearing. “Protect them from significant danger” means that you either prevented them from coming to harm or rescued them from a worse fate. “When time passes and your ward is safe” means that whenever “time passes” and the Woodland’s war progresses, if your ward is more or less safe, you advance."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests.","description":"You can name any NPC, including one you make up from scratch. Do not name a PC. Whomever you choose should be a powerful foe—a real enemy who can return again and again. If you choose someone easily disposed of, then this drive will quickly become irrelevant. “Significant harm” is left up to a conversation between the GM and the players, with the GM having final say."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration.","description":"“Certain death or incarceration” here refers to the overdramatic sense of “dire straits”—obviously, if death were actually certain, then you wouldn’t have escaped! Think of it instead as making a narrow escape from what looks like impossible-to-overcome danger."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing.","description":"This is one of the most direct, simplest drives in the game—every time you arrive at another clearing, you advance. Not when you begin the journey, of course; only when you arrive."},{"name":"Antimilitarist","condition":"Advance when you sabotage a non-denizen faction's armies or their ability to wage war.","description":"\"Sabotage\" can entail burning an army's supplies, wrecking siege weapons, or even falsifying or destroying orders, as long as a faction's military is significantly hampered. A vagabond with this drive is pursuing an end to the War in the Woodland and is enacting that change by ruining every faction's ability to fight, regardless of their politics or beliefs."},{"name":"Atonement","condition":"Advance when you earn forgiveness from someone you or your allies previously harmed.","description":"This drive requires you to prove you understand how you've hurt someone and truly make things right. Simply apologizing for your actions or behavior isn't sufficient proof—you have to mean it and sincerely attempt to remedy the situation. \"Earning forgiveness\" will be different for each person but you can **figure someone out** to try and understand both how they're feeling and what they might want from you. \"Previous harm\" can't be something you just did five seconds ago, and it can't be a mild slight or insult. You might make amends for things that happen during a session, things established in character creation, or consequences of your actions discovered upon returning to a clearing you've previously been to."},{"name":"Development","condition":"Advance when you contribute to a lasting development or improvement to an entire clearing.","description":"Contributing to \"a lasting development or improvement\" can involve actively helping to create a permanent structure, like working with the denizens to build a new mill for a farm, or helping troops reinforce a clearing's decrepit walls. It can also involve creating a permanent opportunity like clearing out a ruin in order for a new structure to be built over it. These upgrades must be for the benefit of the entire clearing, even if everyone in the clearing doesn't agree with it—not every development will be altruistic or universally loved. You don't need to singlehandedly create such an improvement—providing labor, expertise, or supplies all count towards triggering this drive. Whatever the development is, remember that it needs to be \"lasting,\" meaning it should fundamentally change the clearing and become an important location of some kind."},{"name":"Devotion","condition":"Advance when you get a non-believer to share in one of your beliefs or practices.","description":"You follow an organized or folk religion; name it and describe its beliefs. You may choose to follow one of the existing faiths of the Woodland (like the beliefs of the Lizard Cult) or create your own. You don't need to come up with every detail of your religion when you choose this drive—just make note of the most important beliefs and practices your faith asks of you. Think of a few big things that you must (or must not) do, such as \"I must not kill,\" \"I must pray to the Wyrm every morning,\" or \"I must donate to the impoverished.\" When someone outside of your faith willingly joins you in one of those rituals or aspects of your beliefs, you advance. This drive isn't really about proselytizing; it's about sharing your beliefs with others in the hopes that they'll understand and appreciate what you practice."},{"name":"Discord","condition":"Advance when your actions create or intensify a serious conflict between two factions.","description":"Although every faction is always at odds with each other, they aren't always in direct confrontation. You probably don't care who's fighting whom so long as the Woodland is in chaos. \"Creating or intensifying a serious conflict\" goes beyond simple misunderstandings or squabbles—troops are dispatched, roads are blocked, relations sour. A conflict must arise where there wasn't one before, or you need to pour fuel on the fire of an existing feud. The outcome of your subterfuge may be noticeable right away, or you might find out when **time passes** or at the end of a session."},{"name":"Esprit de Corps","condition":"Advance when you win a battle against enemy soldiers alongside friends and allies.","description":"This drive emphasizes a vagabond's pursuit of military camaraderie—it only triggers after winning a battle, specifically against enemy soldiers, and in the presence of friends and allies. \"Enemy soldiers\" means they are real combatants—bandits, a rabble, or a mob wouldn't count. A battle can be any kind of combat engagement but it needs to be some kind of direct confrontation, whether it's a siege or a skirmish in an open field. You don't need to be leading those friends and allies to trigger the drive—as long as you've won the day with comrades-in-arms, you qualify."},{"name":"Folk Hero","condition":"Advance when you perform a significant act of service or heroism on behalf of the denizens.","description":"\"A significant act of service or heroism\" should involve creating some kind of lasting change to a clearing or overcoming a major obstacle. Simply helping one person with their troubles isn't enough to qualify for this drive—your act must make things better for the denizens going forward. Since this must be \"on behalf of the denizens,\" it should be something the denizens actually asked you to do, or your actions should address a real problem of theirs—not just something you *think* is a problem. Just because you *think* Eyrie control of their clearing is a major problem doesn't mean ousting the Eyrie governor qualifies— not when the governor was also providing food for the clearing, and the ouster leaves the clearing in chaos."},{"name":"Glory","condition":"Advance when you defeat a worthy foe in single combat.","description":"\"A worthy foe\" must be an enemy who can believably match or exceed your combat capabilities, and whose defeat is significant or meaningful. If you can be entirely confident you'll win against an opponent, then they're not \"worthy\". \"Worthy\" looks different for each vagabond—a nimble duelist might advance after defeating another skilled, dexterous fighter or a massive brute whose heavy swings make up for their lack of speed. \"In single combat\" means no other vagabond can interfere with your fight."},{"name":"Mysteries","condition":"Advance when you discover the truth behind strange phenomena or goings-on within a clearing.","description":"Whatever unusual activity appears to be going on in a clearing, \"discovering the truth\" means learning what's beneath that facade. You need to find the answer for yourself, whether by unmasking a false monster, locating the source of a \"cursed\" crop blight, or cornering a huckster with evidence and obtaining a confession. \"Strange phenomena or goings-on\" can be anything suspicious or unusual, from the mundane (like suspicious behavior of denizens) to paranormal phenomena with reasonable explanations."},{"name":"Partisan","condition":"Advance when you successfully complete a mission given to you by an important member of that faction.","description":"Name a faction. As a vagabond, you are a deniable asset for each faction but your outsider status means you're never truly seen as one of them. By taking this drive, you indicate you've taken a clear side as a dedicated freelancer for a particular side of the War. \"An important member\" of a faction must hold some position of power or influence, and the most obvious way to pursue this drive is to **meet someone important** and ask for (or be given) an assignment. Missions must be \"given\"—you can't assign yourself a mission, so be sure to talk to important representatives of your chosen faction often! For the MC, \"a mission\" can be just about anything but it should either advance the goals of the vagabond's chosen faction, or the personal goals of whoever gave you the task. A mission is complete when all of its objectives are met, whether or not you immediately report back to your handler."},{"name":"Traveler","condition":"Advance when you replace a valuable or meaningful item with one that represents the local culture.","description":"You can't trigger this drive by ditching your equipment and picking up a replacement off the ground. The equipment you leave behind has to be something valuable to you—it can't be something you might have thrown out anyway because it's not worth the weight to carry. The equipment you replace it with needs to reflect the essential nature of the clearing you're in, or otherwise represent a central aspect of its culture. You might acquire a sword from a clearing known for its fine steelwork, cookware and spices suited to a regional specialty dish, or a musical instrument tied to a clearing's heritage. Whatever equipment you leave behind is of no further use to you, and you become a walking tapestry of the Woodland with each new acquisition."},{"name":"Wanted","condition":"Advance when you defeat or evade capture by a serious threat trying to cash in on your bounty.","description":"You've got a bounty on your head; name your crime(s). If you take this drive at character creation, your background questions probably point to what crimes you're wanted for. If you choose this drive during play, work with the MC to decide who put the bounty out on you and why. Whatever crimes you're wanted for, they're serious enough that you risk capture anywhere you go. \"Evading capture\" means there's a genuine chance you would have been caught by pursuers. \"A serious threat\" has to be truly dangerous and they must be chasing you specifically for your bounty—the MC might send a squad of hardened commandos, a famous detective looking to pad their career, or even a coin-hungry vagabond after you."}],"basicMoves":[{"name":"Attempt a Roguish Feat","category":"Basic","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat you are skilled in, say your goal and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you achieve your goal.","7-9":"On a 7-9, mark exhaustion or one risk of your feat (GM's choice) comes to bear."},"options":[],"notes":"When you attempt a roguish feat you are NOT skilled in, you are trusting fate."},{"name":"Figure Someone Out","category":"Basic","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you try to figure someone out, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, hold 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, hold 1."},"options":["is your character telling the truth?","what is your character really feeling?","what does your character intend to do?","what does your character wish I'd do?","how could I get your character to _______?"],"notes":"While interacting with them, spend your hold 1 for 1 to ask their player a question:"},{"name":"Persuade an NPC","category":"Basic","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you persuade an NPC with promises or threats, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, they see things your way, provided you have given them a strong motive or reasonable bribe.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they aren't sure; the GM will tell you what you need to do to sway them."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Read a Tense Situation","category":"Basic","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you read a tense situation, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"7-9":"On a 7–9, ask 1.","10+":"On a 10+, ask 3.","any":"Take +1 when acting on the answers."},"options":["what's my best way out / in / through?","who or what is the biggest threat?","who or what is most vulnerable to me?","what should I be on the lookout for?","who is in control here?"],"notes":null},{"name":"Trick an NPC","category":"Basic","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you trick an NPC to get what you want, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they take the bait and do what you want.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they can instead choose one:"},"options":["they hesitate; you shake their confidence or weaken their morale.","they stumble; you gain a critical opportunity.","they overreact; take +1 forward against them."],"notes":null},{"name":"Trust Fate","category":"Basic","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you trust fate to get through trouble, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you scrape by or barrel through; the GM will tell you what it costs you.","10+":"On a 10+, fortune favors the bold; your panache also earns you a fleeting opportunity."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Wreck Something","category":"Basic","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you wreck something, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you seriously break it; it can't be used again until it's repaired.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you're imprecise and dangerous; you cause collateral damage, attract attention, or end up in a bad spot, GM's choice."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Help or Interfere","category":"Basic","stat":null,"trigger":"When you help or interfere with another vagabond, mark exhaustion to add +1 or –2 to their roll (after rolling).","outcomes":null,"options":["conceal your help or interference","create an opportunity or obstacle"],"notes":"Mark exhaustion again to select one of the following:"},{"name":"Plead with a PC","category":"Basic","stat":null,"trigger":"When you plead with a PC to go along with you, they clear 1-exhaustion if they agree to what you've proposed.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You may use this move only once per session."},{"name":"Engage in Melee","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you engage an enemy in melee at close or intimate range, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, trade harm.","10+":"On a 10+, pick 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, pick 1."},"options":["inflict serious (+1) harm","suffer little (–1) harm","shift your range one step","impress, dismay, or frighten your foe"],"notes":null},{"name":"Grapple an Enemy","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you grapple with an enemy at intimate range, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you choose simultaneously. Continue making choices until someone disengages, falls unconscious, or dies.","10+":"On a 10+, you make one choice first, before beginning to make simultaneous choices."},"options":["you strike a fast blow; inflict injury","you wear them down; they mark exhaustion","you exploit weakness; mark exhaustion to inflict 2-injury","you withdraw; disengage to close range"],"notes":null},{"name":"Target Someone","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you target a vulnerable foe at far range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you inflict injury.","10+":"On a 10+, you can strike again before they get to cover—inflict injury again—or keep your position hidden, your choice."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Cleave","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you cleave armored foes at close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you smash through their defenses and equipment; inflict 3-wear.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you overextend your weapon or yourself: mark wear or end up in a bad spot, your choice."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"cleave"},{"name":"Confuse Senses","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you throw something to confuse an opponent’s senses at close or intimate range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you’ve thrown them off balance, blinded them, deafened them, or confused them, and given yourself an opportunity.","10+":"On a 10+, they have to take some time to get their bearings and restore their senses before they can act clearly again.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you have just a few moments."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"confuse senses"},{"name":"Disarm","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you target an opponent’s weapon with your strikes at close range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they have to mark 2-exhaustion or lose their weapon—it’s well out of reach.","10+":"On a 10+, they have to mark 3-exhaustion instead of 2."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"disarm"},{"name":"Harry a Group","category":"Weapon","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you harry a group of enemies at far range, mark wear and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, both.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1:"},"options":["inflict 2-morale harm","they are pinned or blocked"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"harry a group"},{"name":"Improvise a Weapon","category":"Weapon","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you make a weapon out of improvised materials around you, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you make a weapon; the GM will tell you its range tag and at least one other beneficial tag based on the materials you used.","7-9":"On a 7–9, the weapon also has a weakness tag."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"improvise a weapon"},{"name":"Parry","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you try to parry the attacks of an enemy at close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you consume their attention.","10+":"On a 10+, all 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, pick 1."},"options":["you inflict morale or exhaustion harm (GM’s choice)","you disarm your opponent; their weapon is out of hand, but in reach","you don’t suffer any harm"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"parry"},{"name":"Quick Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you fire a snap shot at an enemy at close range, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, inflict injury.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2."},"options":["you don’t mark wear","you don’t mark exhaustion","you move quickly and change your position (and, if you choose, range)","you keep your target at bay—they don’t move"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"quick shot"},{"name":"Storm a Group","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you storm a group of foes in melee, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, trade harm.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1."},"options":["you show them up; you inflict 2-morale harm","you keep them off-balance and confused; you inflict 2-exhaustion","you avoid their blows to the best of your ability; you suffer little (–1) harm","you use them against each other; mark exhaustion again and they inflict their harm against themselves"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"storm a group"},{"name":"Trick Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you fire a clever shot designed to take advantage of the environment at any range, mark wear and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 2.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 3."},"options":["your shot lands in any target of your choice within range, even if it’s behind cover or hidden (inflicting injury or wear if appropriate)","your shot strikes a second available target of your choice","your shot cuts something, breaks something, or knocks something over, your choice","your shot distracts an opponent and provides an opportunity"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"trick shot"},{"name":"Vicious Strike","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you viciously strike an opponent where they are weak at intimate or close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they suffer serious (+1) harm and cannot mark wear on their armor to block it.","10+":"On a 10+, you get away with the strike.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they score a blow against you as well."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"vicious strike"},{"name":"Travel Through the Forest","category":"Travel","stat":null,"trigger":"When you **travel from clearing to clearing through the forest**, the band collectively decides how it travels and one member of the band rolls for the group:","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you pass through the forest to any clearing on the other side. Along the way, one of you spots an interesting site; you leave markers so you can return after you finish your trip.","10+":"On a 10+, the transit is largely safe.","7-9":"On a 7–9, something from the forest is following you; you can let it track you, or every vagabond marks exhaustion to lose it.","6-":"On a miss, you run afoul of one of the forest’s dangers during the trip, and you can’t escape it easily; deal with it before you can reach the clearing on the other side."},"options":["slowly, foraging heavily: everyone clears 2-depletion; the band collectively marks an exhaustion for each band member; –1 to the roll","carefully, avoiding trouble: the band collectively marks one depletion or exhaustion for each band member; +1 to the roll","as quickly as possible: everyone marks exhaustion and depletion; +2 to the roll"],"notes":null},{"name":"Travel Along the Path","category":"Travel","stat":null,"trigger":"When you **travel from clearing to clearing along the path**, the band collectively decides how it travels and one member of the band rolls for the group:","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you reach the next clearing in a timely fashion.","10+":"On a 10+, the trip is uninterrupted and quick.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you encounter something noteworthy on the path—a caravan, a battleground, or something else odd passing through.","6-":"On a miss, you are caught in the middle of a dangerous situation before you arrive at the next clearing."},"options":["at a relaxing pace: everyone clears 3-exhaustion; the band collectively marks a total of 2-depletion; –1 to the roll","at an average pace: everyone clears 2-exhaustion; the band collectively marks 1-depletion; +0 to the roll","safely, quickly, and under the radar: the band collectively marks 1-depletion for supplies; +1 to the roll","urgently fast: everyone marks exhaustion; +2 to the roll"],"notes":null},{"name":"End of Session (Advancement)","category":"Session","stat":null,"trigger":"When the session ends, one at a time, each player reads their drives out loud.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"The players and GM discuss whether the player fulfilled their drive during the session in an instance that wasn't already called out during the session. If they did, and they did not already advance this session for the drive in question, then they advance."},{"name":"End of Session (Update Character)","category":"Session","stat":null,"trigger":"When the session ends, one at a time, each player may choose one element of their playbook to update or change.","outcomes":null,"options":["Replace one drive with a new drive from any playbook","Replace nature with a new nature from any playbook","Replace a connection (both type and subject) with a new connection from any playbook"],"notes":"They do not have to choose anything, if they don't want to. They may choose one of the following options:"},{"name":"Ask for a Favor","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **ask for a reasonable favor based on your reputation**, roll with Reputation with the appropriate faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they'll grant you what you want.","7-9":"On a 7–9, it costs your rep a bit; clear prestige or mark notoriety, your choice.","miss":"On a miss, they refuse and view you with suspicion; mark notoriety."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Meet Someone Important","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **meet with someone important for the first time**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you're aware of their wider reputation (if any), and they're aware of yours (if any).","7-9":"On a 7-9, pick one.","10+":"On a 10+, both.","miss":"On a miss, you only know the basics about them, and they've heard stories about you and the things you've done, true or false—prepare for major complications."},"options":["you've heard stories; ask a question about them, and the GM will tell you one story you've heard about them or their interests as an answer.","they've heard something in your favor; take +1 forward when you first try to play up your connection with them and their faction."],"notes":null},{"name":"Draw Attention","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **try to publicly draw attention to yourself as an enemy of a faction**, roll with Reputation for that faction, treating it as positive (+2 or +3) for this roll.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you draw out the faction's resources to oppose you; brace yourself.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 1;","10+":"on a 10+, choose 2.","miss":"On a miss, your enemies are already moving against you quietly; the GM tells you how they catch you unprepared."},"options":["the faction employs significant military strength to chase you down","the faction deploys an available, capable NPC agent (of your choice) to chase you down","the faction is rattled by your threat; mark 2-notoriety with them"],"notes":"REQUIRES –2 OR LOWER REPUTATION"},{"name":"Sway an NPC","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **try to sway an open or vulnerable NPC by appealing to their belief in your reputation**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you can change their mind about the world; say what you want them to believe, and the GM will rewrite their drive accordingly.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you use up some goodwill; clear 3-prestige. If you don't have enough prestige to clear, mark the remainder in notoriety.","miss":"On a miss, the NPC takes the wrong message away from what you say; the GM will rewrite their drive accordingly."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES +2 OR HIGHER REPUTATION"},{"name":"Make a Pointed Threat","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **make a pointed threat to an NPC by wielding your reputation**, roll with Reputation for their faction, treating it as positive (+3) for this roll.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, they are rattled; they must surrender, retreat, or charge, GM's choice.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you must make a demonstration of your dangerous intent first, before they are rattled.","miss":"On a miss, your reputation precedes you; they reveal how they prepared for someone like you."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES -3 REPUTATION"},{"name":"Command Resources","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **command an NPC to give you significant, valuable resources**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, you get what you need as soon as they can get it to you.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they impose a condition on how you can use the resources, or what you must return to the faction in recompense.","miss":"On a miss, they don't have what you need, but they tell you a way you can get it at a steep cost or some serious difficulty."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES +3 REPUTATION"},{"name":"Endorse a New Leader","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you openly endorse an individual as the new leader of a faction's forces and/or presence in a clearing, roll with Reputation with that faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"you throw your support behind that individual and the faction's representatives in that clearing react.","7-9":"the GM chooses 2.","10+":"the GM chooses 1.","6-":"after you publicly announce your support something new and dangerous is revealed about the leadership or the individual you endorsed that reframes the situation."},"options":["the faction's current leadership in the clearing is directly opposed; you need to handle them before your endorsed candidate can take over","the denizens of the clearing aren't on board; you need to speak to denizen leadership and convince them, or expect direct opposition","the faction's enemies in the clearing want to take advantage of the shift in power; keep an eye out for conspiracies and plots"],"notes":"Requires Reputation +1"},{"name":"Vilify a Leader","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you openly vilify an existing leader of a faction's forces and/or presence in a clearing, roll with Reputation with that faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"you've stirred up dissent—the leader's departure from power is set in motion. They will be removed from power when next time passes... unless they take other action (alliances, use of force, etc.) to quash the dissent. In the meantime,","7-9":"the GM chooses 2.","10+":"the GM chooses 1.","6-":"your words wind up stoking opposition—more denizens, agents, and faction members come out in support of the leader you tried to vilify."},"options":["your words are taken up and elaborated upon; resistance to the leader you targeted threatens to get out of control, involving violence or arson","the leader (or their defenders and supporters) grows more radical in their defensiveness; they will respond to any threats to their position with force","you are singled out for your blunt outspokenness; expect reprisals"],"notes":"Requires Reputation +1"},{"name":"Lead Troops in Battle","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you lead troops of a faction in battle, roll with Reputation with that faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"they accept you as their commander for the fight.","7-9":"hold 2.","10+":"hold 3.","6-":"your troops engage in battle but with a confused command structure—they wind up embroiled in chaotic battle across the entire area, and in their confusion, they're losing."},"options":["take and hold a location","rout a substantial enemy presence","take an enemy leader captive","destroy a fortification or resource","defend a group or location"],"notes":"Requires Reputation +3. Spend your hold 1-for-1 during the fight to commit them to:"},{"name":"Intimidate Enemy Troops","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you draw attention to yourself and threaten enemy troops by wielding your Reputation through an intimidating display, roll with Reputation with the enemy's faction, treating it as positive (+2 or +3) for this roll.","outcomes":{"hit":"you put fear into the enemy.","7-9":"pick 1.","10+":"pick 2.","6-":"the enemy is invigorated by their anger at you, and they act right now, in full force."},"options":["the enemy troops won't act until their leader makes a rallying speech or cry to them—the leader is exposed and vulnerable to attack","the enemy troops will target you, above all else, when they attack","the enemy troops are rattled; inflict 2-morale harm on the group"],"notes":"Requires Reputation -2"},{"name":"Plan New Project","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you convince Marquisate officers to begin a new significant project, roll with Reputation with the Marquisate.","outcomes":{"hit":"they begin the project.","7-9":"the GM chooses 3.","10+":"the GM chooses 2.","6-":"the Marquisate cannot undertake your project right now because the Marquisate's resources—and you—are required elsewhere; the GM will tell you why, and where."},"options":["it will take time; check back in after time passes","it requires special resources; the Marquisate agents will tell you what they need","it requires elimination of a threat first; the Marquisate agents will point you at the threat","it can't be quite what you asked for—just something close enough; the Marquisate agents will tell you what form it takes"],"notes":"Requires Marquisate Reputation +2"},{"name":"Wield Bureaucracy","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you wield the bureaucracy of the Eyrie Dynasties to achieve your ends while time passes, roll with Reputation with the Eyrie.","outcomes":{"7-9":"choose 1.","10+":"choose 2.","6-":"the Eyrie's bureaucracy plays back, and you find yourself charged with a duty you hadn't planned on from Eyrie authorities; fulfill it before time passes next, or mark 3-notoriety."},"options":["you gather information from your contacts; ask the GM any three questions about the Woodland, and they will answer truthfully from the Eyrie's perspective","you push the Eyrie to allocate resources just a bit differently; they will deliver some available resource to a clearing of your choice, as long as it makes any sense to do so","you add a stipulation to an upcoming Eyrie attack or action; the soldiers will follow it","you arrange a meeting or audience with any Eyrie individual at a place of your choosing; the GM will tell you when the meeting takes place","you get Eyrie courts to add or repeal a legal requirement within any one Eyrie-controlled clearing; the Eyrie theoretically must follow it"],"notes":"Requires Eyrie Reputation +2"},{"name":"Incite Revolt","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you incite local Woodland Alliance sympathizers and agents to revolt, roll with Reputation with the Woodland Alliance.","outcomes":{"hit":"the revolt is imminent—you have to prepare! It will take place when next time passes.","7-9":"the GM chooses 2.","10+":"the GM chooses 1.","6-":"the revolt fires off *right now*—well before you are ready, and while the opposing forces might be prepared for you. Good luck."},"options":["you need to convince at least one local sympathizer to get important resources or support for the revolt; otherwise, it will fail","you need to weaken, destroy, or incapacitate a specific opposing force; otherwise, the revolt will fail","you need to steal weapons or equipment for local sympathizers; otherwise, the revolt will fail","you need to rally a local group by doing them a favor; otherwise, the revolt will fail"],"notes":"Requires Woodland Alliance Reputation +2"},{"name":"Preach to the Choir","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you preach a sermon with a message to a crowd of Lizard Cultists, roll with Reputation with the Lizard Cult.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3.","7-9":"hold 1.","6-":"the mob hears your message incorrectly, and acts on that belief."},"options":["bring someone forward and deliver them","bring forward goods and offerings (providing you with at least 6-Value)","unite and fight for you, destroying or attacking a target of your choice","repair or defend something of your choice","go quietly back to their lives"],"notes":"Requires Lizard Cult Reputation +2. Spend your hold 1-for-1 to make the crowd:"},{"name":"Conduct Sanctioned Trade","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you write up an exchange of goods or services between any parties and sign it in the name of the Riverfolk Company, roll with Reputation with the Riverfolk Company.","outcomes":{"hit":"you form a proper agreement the Company will uphold, by force if it must—name the parties (including you), their responsibilities and promises, and any extra penalties for breach of contract.","7-9":"Company support—mercenaries, trade embargos, etc.—still comes, but at a cost; when you want a Company agent to help uphold the contract, you'll have to offer a 1-Value bribe before they will act.","10+":"the contract is airtight; provided you have a copy in hand, Company agents will enforce the contract in full.","6-":"your contract has a loophole or error in it; the Riverfolk Company won't enforce it, and it's only a matter of time before a participating party takes advantage."},"options":[],"notes":"Requires Riverfolk Company Reputation +2"},{"name":"Tap Criminal Networks","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you tap the local Corvid Conspiracy networks for a favor, pick your favor from the list below and roll with Reputation with the Corvid Conspiracy.","outcomes":{"7-9":"the Conspiracy fulfills the favor, but leaves a request for you too—a favor for a favor.","10+":"the Conspiracy just leaves a reminder that it might call upon you at some later date.","6-":"your illicit communications with the Conspiracy go awry—someone else gets your request, and they aren't happy."},"options":["illicit goods, left in a hidden drop location for you","assassination, accomplished quietly and without fuss","sabotage, conducted on valuable equipment","blackmail, collected and delivered to you for use","secret intelligence, captured and safely sent to you"],"notes":"Requires Reputation +2 with the Corvid Conspiracy"},{"name":"Requisition Permits","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you requisition permits from the Grand Duchy, roll with Reputation with the Duchy.","outcomes":{"hit":"you can requisition a permit with certain access rights granted. These rights remain legal until when next time passes.","7-9":"choose 2 access rights.","10+":"choose 3.","6-":"a Duchy official comes to interrogate you about your requests for permit; expect undesirable scrutiny."},"options":["you are permitted to travel through Grand Duchy tunnels with the aid of a Duchy guide, allowing you to move between any two clearings connected by tunnels without making a roll","you are permitted to obtain supplies from Grand Duchy caches and citadels with impunity; any time you reach such a cache, you may take up to 4-Value in supplies, no questions asked","you are permitted access to members of Duchy Parliament; you can ask any Duchy outpost for news on their locations, and you can always gain access to them, no questions asked","you are permitted to pass freely and without molestation in Duchy controlled areas, no matter whether you are carrying weapons or obvious contraband or not","you are permitted to act directly against or harm any individuals not openly protected by the Duchy, and any individuals openly protected against the Duchy if you can prove their culpability in a crime"],"notes":"Requires Reputation +2 with the Grand Duchy"},{"name":"Battle Fury","category":"Weapon","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you fling yourself into a fury of weapon, tooth, and claw in an all-out attack at intimate range, mark wear on your weapon and roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, fill your exhaustion track. For each box you mark, inflict 2-injury on your target.","7-9":"On a 7-9, your target also inflicts their harm upon you."},"options":[],"notes":"This move does not require the weapon to be tagged with intimate range; weapons with close range may also be used."},{"name":"Charge","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you charge at an opponent at far range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they must choose to either mark 2-exhaustion or allow you to push them—you say where they are driven, and you say what range you now stand at.","10+":"On a 10+, inflict morale harm on them as well."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Hurl","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you hurl a weapon or dangerous object not intended for throwing at an enemy at far range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, your hurled weapon strikes your target; mark wear on the weapon and inflict 1-injury and 1-exhaustion on your target.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 1.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2."},"options":["mark an additional wear on the hurled item to inflict an additional 1-injury","the hurled item rebounds to somewhere reachable, instead of out of sight or out of reach","your target is knocked off their feet by the throw"],"notes":"No weapon tag is required to use this weapon skill."},{"name":"Lunge","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you make an outright lunge at a foe within close range, choose an amount of injury between 1-injury and 3-injury and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you inflict that amount of injury—ignoring armor—but if your target survives (or if other foes are present) they can take advantage of your overextension to inflict the same amount on you.","7-9":"On a 7-9, they can inflict 1-injury more upon you than you had originally chosen to inflict upon them."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Paired Fighting","category":"Weapon","stat":null,"trigger":"When you and another vagabond pair fight back to back against foes at close range, you each mark exhaustion and one of you rolls with the following modifiers (max +3):","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you together inflict 1-injury on every foe within close range (or 3-injury total against a group), and you each suffer 1-injury.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 1.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2."},"options":["you each suffer little (-1) harm","you inflict an additional 2-injury to any single target (including a single group) of your choice","you inflict 2-morale harm","you create a path for the two of you to retreat or advance"],"notes":"+1 if you have a connection with each other; +1 if you are outnumbered; +1 for every 2 additional exhaustion you mark between the two of you"},{"name":"Hammerpaws","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you come to blows with an armed opponent at close or intimate range while you are unarmed, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they inflict their harm on you.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 2.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 3."},"options":["you inflict 2-exhaustion on your opponent","you shift your range one step","you deflect some of their incoming blows; suffer little (-1) harm","you inflict wear on their equipment with precise strikes","you take an object from them; they must mark exhaustion to stop you"],"notes":"No weapon tag is required to use this weapon skill."},{"name":"Pinpoint Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you take the time to fire a shot at far range with pinpoint accuracy, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you put the shot exactly where you choose:","7-9":"On a 7-9, your current vantage point isn't quite right; you need to move to a better one before you can make the perfect shot. Mark exhaustion to scramble there, and then choose as normal."},"options":["if you target an NPC's weak point, inflict 3-injury (unblockable by armor)","if you target a piece of equipment's weak point, inflict 2-wear","if you target something in the environment, you strike it, cut it, or break it as appropriate"],"notes":null},{"name":"Long Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you pull hard on your bow's draw to extend its range beyond far, mark wear and exhaustion to roll any far range weapon move (target someone, pinpoint shot, etc.) with Might instead of the move's normal stat, paying the additional cost(s) of the weapon move as well.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"This weapon skill requires your weapon to be tagged with far range, this skill, and the tag for whatever weapon move you are using (if needed)."},{"name":"Point-Blank Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you fire a shot at point-blank range (intimate range), mark any combination of up to 2-wear and up to 2-exhaustion, and roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you put your shot into your target; inflict injury equivalent to the wear and exhaustion you marked, combined.","10+":"On a 10+, you can also skip back after your shot, moving to close range before your opponent can grab you or otherwise retaliate."},"options":[],"notes":"Your weapon does not need to be tagged with intimate range to use this weapon skill."},{"name":"Switch Hands","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you shift your grip to change your dominant hand in the middle of an extended bout with a foe, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 1.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2:"},"options":["your new dominant hand is fresher; clear 2-exhaustion","your opponent is startled by the shift; they mark morale harm","your shift gives you an immediate opportunity; mark exhaustion to seize it and inflict 2-injury"],"notes":null}],"roguishFeats":[{"name":"Acrobatics","description":"Adeptly climbing, vaulting, jumping","risks":["Break something","detection","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Blindside","description":"Backstab, murder, sneak attack, sucker punch","risks":["Draw unwanted attention","leave evidence","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Counterfeit","description":"Copying, forgery, fakery","risks":["Leave evidence","take too long","weak result"]},{"name":"Disable Device","description":"Disarming traps, turning off mechanisms","risks":["Break something","draw unwanted attention","expend resources"]},{"name":"Hide","description":"Disappear from view, remain hidden","risks":["Expend resources","leave evidence","take too long"]},{"name":"Pick Lock","description":"Open a locked door, chest, etc.","risks":["Break something","detection","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Pickpocket","description":"Subtly steal from a pocket","risks":["Leave evidence","take too long","weak result"]},{"name":"Sleight of Hand","description":"Palming, switching, ditching, flourishes","risks":["Draw unwanted attention","leave evidence","weak result"]},{"name":"Sneak","description":"Get into or out of places without being seen","risks":["Break something","draw unwanted attention","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Cover Up","description":"Rolling unconscious guards into bushes where they won't be found, re-arranging a murder scene to look like an accident (or vice versa), obfuscating signs that the band was ever here—any attempt to remove evidence of roguish activity, or otherwise make a scene appear to be something it isn't, falls under this feat. Any attempt to Cover Up allows a vagabond to control the narrative about the truth of a scene, making an observer believe whatever the vagabond wants, so long as the vagabond has enough time to set up the scene. What separates a Cover Up feat from **tricking an NPC** comes down to the time and precision involved. Tricks are immediate and often improvised, whereas a Cover Up feat requires more moving pieces to craft a believable facade. That doesn't mean a Cover Up feat can't be quick or reactive—if another vagabond leaves some evidence of their actions, a vagabond with this feat can try to make it go away but runs the risk of getting caught in the act.","risks":["Detection","expend resources","take too long"]},{"name":"Mastermind","description":"Organizing the band into position to launch a heist, directing denizens to form a fire brigade, leading an allied squad in a perfectly-timed pincer attack—any attempt to give commands or make tactical decisions falls under the Mastermind feat. Once a vagabond gathers information or **reads a tense situation**, they can use this feat to create tactical plans and direct others through nigh-military command. The main advantage you get through the use of this move is positioning your allies exactly where they need to be to be of greatest use. A hit with the Mastermind feat can act as a kind of prep that means anyone in the plan is exactly where they need to be—at least until the plan is derailed.\n\nThis isn't a substitute for trying to **persuade an NPC**; Mastermind won't work with individuals or groups who aren't already likely to listen to you. Mastermind roguish feats can only be attempted if you already have the attention of—and influence over—the people you're ordering around. Remember, if they wouldn't already listen to you, you can't attempt this feat! Mastermind feats can also cover getting people and things into the right place at the right time, especially if using the flashback rules on page 71 of the Root: The RPG core book.","risks":["Draw unwanted attention","plunge into danger","take too long"]},{"name":"Set Trap","description":"Brushing branches and leaves over a hastily-dug pit trap, wedging timed Corvid explosives under a bridge, keeping your bow ready while providing overwatch from a hidden position—any attempt to create a trap or an opportunity for a surprise attack falls under the Set Trap roguish feat. Whenever a vagabond might **trust fate** to lay a trap for someone, a skilled vagabond can use this feat to do so with far more precision. Set Trap can sometimes bypass an attempt at the Blindside roguish feat, but only if it affects a single target, and if the fiction supports the situation. For example, if you set a snare and **trick** a single foe into crossing over it, then they might be taken out all at once. Anything beyond the scope of a single-individual-oriented trap can be staged with this feat but you have to Blindside to actually capitalize on your preparation. Think of it a bit like Hiding before Blindsiding. For example, a vagabond can prepare a roadside ambush for a group with a Set Trap feat, lining up mostly-sawed trees to fall in the road and block their retreat, and then attempt a Blindside feat to rain arrows down on their quarries. This feat only covers ambushes and traps— setting something to fail or misfire is more likely a Disable Device feat if it's done carefully, or **wrecking something** if it's fast and furious.","risks":["Detection","expend resources","leave evidence"]},{"name":"Tracking","description":"Pursuing a mark through rain-soaked alleys, tracking a bear back to their lair, determining soldiers' movements by boot prints—any attempt to pursue or track down someone falls under the Tracking roguish feat. Tracking is about the actual act of finding and following others, not about staying hidden or staying out of sight—like the Hide or Sneak roguish feats—although a complication or miss will likely lead to those feats in order to keep one's cover.","risks":["Detection","plunge into danger","take too long"]},{"name":"Use Device","description":"Driving a clockwork logging contraption, activating a ruin's flamespitting statues to repel rivals, banking a hang glider into thick foliage to evade Eyrie commandos on your tail—any attempt to control or activate machines or devices falls under this feat. Whereas Disable Device is about breaking a device or stopping its effects, Use Device is about making a contraption work for you. A vagabond with this feat has a knack for mechanics even if they're not a Tinker; they can figure things out on the fly, even if they've never seen how something works before. This feat also covers attempts to maneuver vehicles. Instead of **trusting fate** to steer a raft through rapids or jump a minecart over a gaping chasm, a vagabond can attempt to Use Device.","risks":["Break something","plunge into danger","weak result"]}],"equipment":[{"name":"Dagger","value":5,"load":0,"wear":0,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Parry","vicious strike","+Quick: Mark exhaustion to engage in melee with Finesse instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Mousefolk Short Sword","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","disarm","+Mousefolk Steel: Mark wear to engage in melee using Cunning instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Foxfolk Longsword","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Disarm","vicious strike","+Foxfolk Steel: Ignore the first box of wear you mark on this item each session."],"description":null},{"name":"Rabbitfolk Axe","value":4,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Disarm","+Rabbitfolk Steel: Mark wear to engage in melee with Finesse instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Greatsword","value":6,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Cleave","storm a group","disarm","+Sharp: Mark wear when inflicting harm with this weapon to inflict 1 additional harm.","+Large: Mark exhaustion when inflicting harm with this weapon to inflict 1 additional harm.","-Bulky: This weapon cannot be hidden and is always visible while on your body. Mark exhaustion whenever you attempt a roguish feat or trust fate to sneak, hide, blindside, or perform an act of acrobatics."],"description":null},{"name":"Smithy Hammer","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Cleave","+Heavy Bludgeon: Mark exhaustion to ignore your enemy's armor when you inflict harm."],"description":null},{"name":"Staff","value":4,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","+Blunted: This weapon inflicts exhaustion, not injury."],"description":null},{"name":"Spear","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","+Reach: When you engage in melee, mark wear on this weapon to inflict harm instead of trading harm; you cannot use this tag if your enemy's weapon also has reach.","+Blunted: This weapon inflicts exhaustion, not injury."],"description":null},{"name":"Shortbow","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Quick shot","+Short Limbs: Mark wear to fire a quick shot at far range."],"description":null},{"name":"Longbow","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Far","tags":["Harry a group"],"description":null},{"name":"Trick Bow","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Harry","trick shot"],"description":null},{"name":"Crossbow","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Far","tags":["Trick shot","+Oiled String: Mark wear to use the weapon skill quick shot even if you don't have it.","+Hair Trigger: Mark wear to target a vulnerable foe at close range instead of far.","+Iron Bolts: This weapon inflicts 1 additional wear when its harm is absorbed by armor."],"description":null},{"name":"Sling","value":3,"load":0,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Harry a group"],"description":null},{"name":"Leather Armor","value":3,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Flexible: When you grapple with someone, mark exhaustion to ignore the first choice they make."],"description":null},{"name":"Chainmail","value":3,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Tightly Woven: When you take a few seconds to repair this armor after a fight, clear 1-wear you marked during the fight.","-Weighty: This item counts as 1 additional Load."],"description":null},{"name":"Plate Armor","value":3,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Arrow-proof: Ignore the first hit dealing injury from arrows that you suffer in a scene.","-Cumbersome: Mark 1-exhaustion when you don your armor—clear 1-exhaustion when you take it off.","-Weighty: This item counts as 1 additional Load"],"description":null},{"name":"Robes","value":2,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Unassuming: Until you harm an enemy, they will never deem you more of a threat than other vagabonds with arms and armor."],"description":null},{"name":"Lizard Cult Ritual Blade","value":3,"load":0,"wear":null,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Vicious strike","+Intimidating","-Incriminating","-Scarce"],"description":null},{"name":"Spring-loaded Wristblade","value":6,"load":0,"wear":null,"range":"Intimate","tags":["Vicious strike","+Hidden","+Accurate"],"description":null},{"name":"Spiked Flail/Chain","value":5,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Storm a group","Cleave","+Impressive","-Dangerous"],"description":null},{"name":"Dueling Rapier","value":6,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Disarm","Parry","+Precise","+Quick","-Fragile"],"description":null},{"name":"Bird Talon Gauntlets","value":4,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Vicious strike","+Nasty","-Immoral"],"description":null},{"name":"Riverboat Paddle","value":2,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Storm a group","+Blunted","-Hard to Hold","-Unwieldy"],"description":null},{"name":"Stiletto Dagger","value":5,"load":0,"wear":null,"range":"Intimate","tags":["Vicious strike","+Precise","+Hidden"],"description":null},{"name":"Polearm","value":6,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Cleave","Disarm","+Common","+Reach","-Bulky"],"description":null},{"name":"Sword Cane","value":6,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","Disarm","+Disguised","+Quick","-Hard to Hold"],"description":null},{"name":"Blade of the Last Dynasty / Sword of the True King","value":12,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","Vicious strike","+Legendary","+Eaglecraft","+Luxury","-Identifiable"],"description":null},{"name":"Bear Skull Helmet","value":2,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Impressive","-Cursed"],"description":null},{"name":"Spiked Shield","value":4,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Nasty","+Distracting"],"description":null},{"name":"Heavy Gambeson","value":2,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Reinforced"],"description":null},{"name":"Scavenged Armor","value":2,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Disarming","-Makeshift"],"description":null},{"name":"Collapsible Paraglider","value":4,"load":2,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Thief Kit","+Sturdy","-Weighty"],"description":null},{"name":"Libelous Documents","value":3,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Incendiary","-Incriminating"],"description":null},{"name":"Forest Cloak","value":3,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Blend"],"description":null},{"name":"Portable Easel & Paints","value":4,"load":2,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Cathartic","-Weighty"],"description":null},{"name":"Corvid Explosives","value":2,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Mighty","-Noisy"],"description":null},{"name":"Belt of Smoke Bombs","value":4,"load":0,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Thief Kit","+Light"],"description":null},{"name":"Masterwork Instrument","value":6,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Inspiring","+Signature"],"description":null},{"name":"Performer's Garb","value":4,"load":1,"wear":null,"range":null,"tags":["+Disarming","+Distracting"],"description":null}],"advancement":{"trigger":"Advance by following your nature or achieving a drive.","options":[{"name":"Take +1 to a stat (max +2)","description":"Add +1 to one of your stats! The highest it can go through this advancement is a +2, but there are moves you can take from several playbooks that can boost it to a +3."},{"name":"Take a new move from your playbook (max 5 moves from your own playbook)","description":"Check another box and gain another one of your own playbook’s moves! The majority of playbooks start with three moves already, so you can usually only take this advancement twice."},{"name":"Take a new move from another playbook (max 2 moves from other playbooks)","description":"You have access to the whole range of moves available in other playbooks. It’s a lot to look through, so unless you have something specific in mind you might want to take suggestions from the other players and GM, or look through the other playbooks during downtime. You can only take this advancement twice, for two total moves from other playbooks."},{"name":"Take up to two new weapon skills (max 7 total)","description":"Check off the boxes and learn two more weapon skills! Spend a bit of time thinking about from where you learned these skills—was it a teacher, or just practice, practice, practice? The maximum seven total weapon skills counts the weapon skills you start the game with, but it does NOT count any of the weapon skills you might learn as the result of a playbook move."},{"name":"Take up to two new roguish feats (max 6 total)","description":"Check off the boxes and learn two new roguish feats! Remember that means that you’ll use attempt a roguish feat and Finesse (by default) for those actions instead of trusting fate and Luck—but with the benefit that attempting a roguish feat is a lot less risky and messy than trusting fate. Like with the weapon skills, think a bit about how you learned these feats. The maximum six total roguish feats includes those you start with, but does NOT include any you might learn as the result of a playbook move."},{"name":"Add one box to any one harm track (max 6 each)","description":"Expand your harm track—give yourself greater reserves of energy (Exhaustion), bigger pockets (Depletion), or more toughness (Injury)! Each track can only increase to six boxes, though you can ultimately increase all three tracks to six boxes. This does NOT count any additional boxes you might earn as the result of a playbook move like Big Pockets (page 162)."},{"name":"Take up to two new connections (max 6 total)","description":"Take two new connections—just the mechanics, like Protector or Watcher. See page 51 for the full list of connection types. This advancement is mostly for larger vagabond bands, in which you might have a lot of companions and want a connection to each, or for when you feel very strongly that your relationship with a single vagabond has become multifaceted and thus deserving of two connections pointed at the same character."}]},"playbooks":[{"name":"The Adventurer","blurb":"You are a peaceful, diplomatic vagabond, making allies from those you aid, perhaps toppling greater powers by forging strong bonds with others.\n\nPleasant, persuasive, renowned, peaceful. The Adventurer is a speaker and negotiator, trying to resolve conflicts and better the Woodland through honest speech and genuine pleas.\n\nAs the Adventurer, you are a capable talker with a tendency towards nonviolence and resolution of conflicts through negotiation. You might be driven by a general tendency to help those in need, by the goal of rising in renown, or by a specific desire to fix the larger Woodland—but one way or another, you're interested in being viewed positively.\n\nYour fellow vagabonds will likely want to resolve things a bit more directly than you, focusing on combat, thievery, or deception to get what they desire. But in the long run, you are much more likely to achieve positive results; combat, thievery, and deception tend to have consequences, even if you get away scotfree in the moment.\n\nYour natures, \"Extrovert\" and \"Peacemaker,\" both point at your penchant for conversational interaction with other characters, your talent for relationship building. Focus on your interactions with other characters, PCs and NPCs alike.\n\nLook for chances to resolve situations by talking, without using violence, and don't shy away from risky situations. Your fellow vagabonds might have to come in to bail you out, but that's all for the best, making a more interesting game and giving everyone a chance to shine. Use your other skills and connections to support your fellow vagabonds if it does come to blows—if nothing else, assessing the situation is always pretty useful.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":0,"Might":-1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Extrovert","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you share a moment of real warmth, friendship, or enjoyment with someone."},{"name":"Peacemaker","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you resolve a dangerous conflict nonviolently."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."}],"connections":["Partner: _________ and I fought alongside each other to defend a clearing from a faction's advances...but we failed. Why did we defend the clearing? Why did we fail? Who defeated us?","Friend: I traveled with _________ for a time right after I became a vagabond. They helped keep me safe and showed me the Woodland. What keepsake did I gift them?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Sterling Reputation","trigger":"Whenever you mark any amount of prestige with a faction, mark one additional prestige.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"When you mark any amount of notoriety with a faction, you can instead clear an equivalent amount of marked prestige."},{"name":"Subduing Strikes","trigger":"When you aim to subdue an enemy quickly and nonlethally, you can engage in melee with Cunning instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You cannot choose to inflict serious harm if you do.","stat":"Cunning"},{"name":"Talon on the Pulse","trigger":"When you gather information about the goings-on in a clearing, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"ask 3.","7-9":"ask 2.","6-":"your questions tip off someone dangerous."},"options":["Who holds power in this clearing?","Who is the local dissident?","What are the denizens afraid of?","What do the denizens hope for?","What opportunities exist for enterprising vagabonds?"],"notes":null,"stat":"Cunning"},{"name":"Orator","trigger":"When you give a speech to interested denizens of a clearing, say what you are motivating them to do and roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they will move to do it as they see fit.","10+":"choose 2.","7-9":"choose 1.","6-":"they twist your message in unpredictable ways."},"options":["They don't try to take your intent too far","They don't disband at the first sign of real resistance","They don't demand you stand at their head and lead"],"notes":null,"stat":"Charm"},{"name":"Well-Read","trigger":"Take +1 Cunning (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Fast Friends","trigger":"When you try to befriend an NPC you've just met by matching their personality, body language, and desires, mark exhaustion and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"they'll look upon you favorably—ask them any one noncompromising question and they'll answer truthfully, or request a simple favor and they'll do it for you.","10+":"they really like you—they'll share a valuable secret or grant you a serious favor instead.","6-":"you read them totally wrong, and their displeasure costs you."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Cunning"}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Sleight of Hand"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Disarm","Harry","Improvise","Parry"]},"startingValue":9,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Arbiter","blurb":"You are a powerful, obstinate vagabond, serving as somewhere between a mercenary and a protector, perhaps taking sides too easily in the greater conflict between the factions.\n\nJust, mighty, committed, defensive. The Arbiter is a capable warrior and protector, intervening in conflicts on one side or another, defending the innocent and punishing the transgressors.\n\nAs the Arbiter, you are one of the most competent fighters among your vagabond brethren, with a tendency to act like a wandering knight—a force of martial prowess without a single specific cause, but with a sense of justice all your own.\n\nOther powers and figures are likely to want you on their side. After all, you are one of the best warriors they could have fighting for them! A key question for the Arbiter is always \"On whose side do you fight?\" Maybe you defend the innocent from tyrants, but maybe you pick the side you think is most likely to bring about peace.\n\nYour natures, \"Defender\" and \"Punisher,\" speak to the two sides of the Arbiter—one as a protector keeping harm from your wards, and the other as an avenger pursuing justice against wrongdoers. Both of them are likely to aim you at dangerous and powerful foes, so be on the lookout for antagonists who are targeting other denizens (so you can protect them) or who are deserving of justice.\n\nTry to find causes to fight for or against. You're skilled at fighting, but if you only wait for fights to come to you, you might find yourself waiting more than you'd like. And don't hesitate to use other skills like Carry a Big Stick to try to avoid fights—you're skilled at fighting, but martial conflict almost always creates new problems.","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":0,"Luck":-1,"Might":2},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Defender","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put yourself in harm's way to defend someone against injustice or dire threat."},{"name":"Punisher","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you tell a powerful or dangerous villain to their face that you will punish them."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Protector: I once protected _________ from a mortal blow during a fight, and I would do it again. Why?","Partner: _________ and I together helped a faction take control of a clearing, and share responsibility for it."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Brute","trigger":"","outcomes":{"any":"Take +1 Might (max +3)."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Carry a Big Stick","trigger":"When you use words to pause an argument or violent conflict between others, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they choose: mark 2-exhaustion and keep going, or stop for now.","10+":"take +1 ongoing to dealing with them peacefully.","miss":"NPCs turn their anger to you, and PCs take +1 ongoing against you for the scene."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Charm"},{"name":"Crash and Smash","trigger":"When you smash your way through scenery to reach someone or something, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"you reach your target.","10+":"choose 1.","7-9":"choose 2.","miss":"you smash through, but you leave yourself totally vulnerable on the other side."},"options":["You hurt yourself: mark 1 injury","You break an important part of your surroundings","You damage or leave behind a piece of gear (GM's choice)"],"notes":null,"stat":"Might"},{"name":"Hardy","trigger":"","outcomes":{"any":"Take 1 additional injury box. Whenever time passes or you journey to a new clearing, you can clear 2 injury boxes automatically."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Strong Draw","trigger":"When you target someone with a bow, mark wear on the bow to roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"mark exhaustion to inflict 1 additional injury. Mark exhaustion again to make your shot ignore the enemy's armor—they cannot mark wear to absorb the injury."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Might"},{"name":"Guardian","trigger":"When you defend someone or something from an immediate NPC or environmental threat, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"you keep them safe and choose one.","7-9":"it costs: expose yourself to danger or escalate the situation.","miss":"you take the full brunt of the blow intended for your protectee, and the threat has you where it wants you."},"options":["Draw the attention of the threat; they focus on you now","Put the threat in a vulnerable spot; take +1 forward to counterstrike","Push the threat back; you and your protectee have a chance to maneuver or flee"],"notes":null,"stat":"Might"}],"startingRoguishFeats":[],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Disarm","Parry","Storm a Group"]},"startingValue":10,"roguishFeatsChoose":1},{"name":"The Harrier","blurb":"You are a quick, enterprising vagabond, racing easily from building to building and clearing to clearing without anything stopping you, perhaps finding yourself in places others would rather keep secret or hidden.\n\nMobile, crafty, unbound, criminal. The Harrier is a moving, traveling vagabond, often specializing as a freelancer for other powers. When they need something smuggled in or out of a clearing, they'll turn to the Harrier.\n\nAs the Harrier, you have a lot of useful skills, and you should seek opportunities to apply them. You're not as obvious a mercenary as a warrior like the Arbiter, but plenty of black marketeers would love to have a Harrier on their payroll.\n\nThe Harrier is very effective at getting jobs and other tasks from NPCs, but is just as effective at finding their own opportunities to take advantage of alongside their fellow vagabonds. As the Harrier, don't be afraid of trying to betray greater powers for some gain or profit—it will often fit your drives perfectly.\n\nYour natures, \"Dutiful\" and \"Competitive,\" both incentivize taking action—doing over planning or thinking. Dutiful incentivizes taking on jobs on behalf of others, so don't hesitate to figure out what NPCs want and ask them for work. Competitive incentivizes taking on risks—it's easy enough to hit Competitive in the middle of any job. Both of them shine a light on the Harrier's emphasis on constantly moving.\n\nFor the Harrier, your drives are even more crucial—if you're ever looking for the next big thing to do, look at your drives and focus on that. But you can easily get by supporting other vagabonds in their goals, especially because it's often easy to hitch your drives and your nature to their objectives.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":2,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Dutiful","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take on a dangerous or difficult task on behalf of another."},{"name":"Competitive","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take dramatically unnecessary risks to show off."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Professional: ___________ and I tried to blaze a new trail between two clearings; without the support of the major factions, it never fully came to fruition.","Friend: ___________ and I forged a bond while investigating a ruin deep in the woods. What strange minor trinkets do each of you carry from that expedition?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Cross Country","trigger":"Take one extra box of exhaustion. When your exhaustion track is full and you must mark exhaustion, you may choose to mark an equivalent amount of injury instead of being removed from the situation or going unconscious.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Fleet of Foot and Hand","trigger":"Take +1 Finesse (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Don't Shoot the Messenger","trigger":"Take the Counterfeit roguish feat (it does not count against your limit.) When you pretend to be an innocuous messenger carrying a missive of import to trick someone, roll with Luck instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Luck"},{"name":"Parkour","trigger":"When you dash your way through a chaotic scene or fight, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3.","7-9":"hold 2. Spend your hold 1-for-1 to dash to something within sight and reach without being stopped, or to dash away from something nearby without being stopped. You can dash away from an enemy even at the moment they attack.","miss":"your surroundings trip you up, and you're caught in place while danger closes in."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Finesse"},{"name":"Traveler Extraordinaire","trigger":"When you travel along the paths to another clearing, you can always give +1 to the roll or clear 2-exhaustion, your choice. When you travel through the forest to another clearing, you can always give +1 to the roll or clear 2-depletion, your choice. In both cases, before you arrive at the next clearing, you can ask the GM any two questions about the next clearing, based on what you remember from your last time through.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Smuggler's Path","trigger":"You've got a good sense for finding secret paths and doors. When you spend time looking for a secret way in or out of a place that might have one, mark exhaustion and roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"you find a hidden path—the GM will detail it and to where it leads.","10+":"there's something along or inside the path of value to you—the GM will tell you what.","miss":"you find a secret path...and someone else is using it right this second. They probably won't be happy you found their secret."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Luck"}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Sneak"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Disarm","Harry","Quick Shot","Trick Shot"]},"startingValue":9,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Ranger","blurb":"You are a capable, stealthy vagabond, centered on the forests that fill the Woodland between the clearings, more interested in the wilds than in the company of other Woodland denizens or their society.\n\nSolitary, dangerous, stealthy, wild. The Ranger is an experienced forestdwelling vagabond, capable of fighting and surviving in the Woodland's most dangerous spaces.\n\nAs the Ranger, you are a skilled and dangerous fighter, but your emphasis is on stealth—striking from shadows, escaping from dangerous conflicts, and more. You can handle yourself in a straight-up fight, but it's likely not your preferred form of conflict.\n\nAt heart, the Ranger is a bit more of a loner than the rest of the vagabonds, but they have found the advantages of the band drawing them in. Companionship, teamwork, shared burdens—these things will always draw the Ranger back to the band. You can play them as gruff and standoffish as you want, but remember that the Ranger belongs with the band as long as they are a PC.\n\nYour natures, \"Loner\" and \"Cynic,\" point to your antisocial behaviors. Loner is obviously pointed at your tendency to try to solve problems alone—keep in mind that it's going to cause you trouble, and that it's about individual situations, not leaving your band behind and journeying to another clearing altogether. Cynic draws attention to your desire to speak truth to power, to question assumptions of the factions and powers that be…but in ways very likely to draw the ire of those very same powers.\n\nLean into your connections and your fellow vagabonds. Your drives and your nature might draw you into conflicts that seem isolated, but they're always more fun when the other PCs can get involved eventually, even if they mostly end up rescuing you!","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Loner","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation alone, without backup or assistance."},{"name":"Cynic","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly and directly ask dangerous questions about an accepted \"truth\"."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Watcher: I was tricked, conned, or deceived by ___________ once. Why do I choose to continue working with them?","Protector: I did something that would have gotten me the enmity of a Woodland faction—if ___________ hadn't covered for me. What did I do? Why and how did they protect me? Regardless, I feel indebted to them."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Silent Paws","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat to sneak or hide, you can mark 2-exhaustion to shift a miss to a 7-9.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You are adept at slipping into and out of dangerous situations without anyone noticing."},{"name":"Slip Away","trigger":"When you take advantage of an opening to escape from a dangerous situation, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you get away.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 1.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 2:","6-":"On a miss, you escape, but it costs you—mark injury or exhaustion, GM's choice—and you leave ample evidence behind for your foes to track and follow you."},"options":["You suffer injury or exhaustion (GM's choice) during your escape","You end up in another dangerous situation","You leave something important behind"],"notes":null,"stat":"Finesse"},{"name":"Poisons and Antidotes","trigger":"When you brew a poison, mark depletion and say what effect you want it to have: sleep, weakness, inebriation, or death.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You have expertise in the poisons and antidotes of the Woodland. Any poison you make requires ingestion or injection; you can use the poison on your weapon or put it in your target's food or drink. When you study a poison or its effects to make an antidote, the GM will tell you what special ingredient you'll need. Get the ingredient and mark depletion to brew the antidote."},{"name":"Forager","trigger":"When you travel or pass into a forest, before making any travel move, you can clear your choice of:","outcomes":null,"options":["Up to 3-depletion","Up to 2-exhaustion","Up to 2-injury"],"notes":null},{"name":"Threatening Visage","trigger":"When you persuade an NPC with open threats or naked steel, roll with Might instead of Charm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Might"},{"name":"Dirty Fighter","trigger":"Take two of the following weapon skills: Trick Shot, Confuse Senses, Improvise Weapon, Disarm, Vicious Strike.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"None of the skills you take with this move count against your limit."}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Hide","Sneak"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Disarm","Harry","Vicious Strike"]},"startingValue":9,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Ronin","blurb":"You are a skilled, willful vagabond, formerly a servant of a lord in a different land, now masterless. You came to the Woodland to live as a free vagabond.\n\nWell-trained, willful, expatriate, free. The Ronin is a former servant and warrior of some master in a land far from here, now broken from their lord and come to this land as a free agent.\n\nAs the Ronin, you are quite a capable fighter, but you're also a social character—a \"servant\" well used to figuring out the vagaries of the court, the needs of a lord, and the ways of propriety. You're at home both on the battlefield and in the halls of power.\n\nThe Ronin, by definition, is originally from somewhere other than the Woodland. They left that life behind with the demise of their master—one of the background questions on the playbook is all about what happened to that master. As such, the Ronin has a different cultural background with different traditions and ideas than a Woodland denizen.\n\nThat said, the Ronin is still a denizen like the other characters. They have the same overarching drives and desires. And the Ronin certainly has been in the Woodland long enough to be able to easily function there, though NPCs recognizing the Ronin's background and treating them differently can make for dramatic trouble (if everyone at the table is on board with those issues coming to the fore).\n\nIn playing a Ronin, be sure to avoid some of the pitfalls of playing a character of a different culture—no accents, no silly misunderstandings about commonplace objects, no broken grammatical constructions. The Ronin is competent and capable, and they've learned how to navigate the Woodland.","stats":{"Charm":0,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":-1,"Might":2},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Survivor","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to flee or cover allies' flight from a dangerous or overwhelming situation."},{"name":"Pilgrim","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you find an expert in a skill you don't possess."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Partner: __________ and I worked together on my first real task of significance in the Woodland, deposing a dangerous authority figure of a faction. Who did we depose? Why?","Watcher: I see in ____________ many reminders of my old master. I am drawn to them, even as I watch them carefully. What is it that reminds me of my old master? How do they feel about my watchful eyes?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Always Armed","trigger":"When you deal harm with an improvised weapon, deal +1 harm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Take the weapon skill Improvise a Weapon (it does not count against your limit). When you deal harm with an improvised weapon, deal +1 harm."},{"name":"Knowing a Lord's Will","trigger":"When you figure out a denizen of status, authority, or power, roll with Might instead of Charm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"When you trick a denizen of status, authority, or power by playing subordinate, roll with Might instead of Cunning.","stat":"Might"},{"name":"Well-Mannered","trigger":"When you enter a social environment dependent on manners and etiquette, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3","7-9":"hold 2","miss":"the rules of etiquette here are far different from what you expected; mark exhaustion as you commit a gravely impolite error."},"options":["Cover up a social faux pas on behalf of yourself or an ally; clear 1-exhaustion","Call out someone else's social faux pas; inflict 1-morale harm on them","Charm someone; take +1 ongoing to speak to them while you have hold","Demonstrate your value; mark prestige with a powerful denizen's faction"],"notes":"Lose all hold when you leave or when social rules fall apart. Spend hold 1-for-1 to:","stat":"Cunning"},{"name":"Fealty","trigger":"When you commit yourself to the cause of someone you deem worthy, swear an oath to them stating what task you will complete on their behalf.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Mark exhaustion to reroll a move made in pursuit of that task. You cannot commit yourself to another cause until you accomplish the first, or break your oath. If you break your oath, fill your exhaustion track and mark 4-notoriety with the faction whose trust you betrayed. If you fulfill your oath, mark 4-prestige with the faction whose trust you kept."},{"name":"The Rules of War","trigger":"When you call upon a reasonable foe to uphold a rule of war, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"they feel obliged; choose one below they must follow.","7-9":"they choose one that you must follow; disobey, and the obligation ends.","miss":"they feel no obligation to your ideas of war; prepare for a brutal lesson in the rules they adhere to."},"options":["Show mercy to surrendering foes and prisoners","Refrain from underhanded tactics in a fight","Face each other without aid, back-up, or assistance","Keep the violence away from the unarmed or innocent","Fight to surrender or subdual, without retreat"],"notes":null,"stat":"Might"},{"name":"Always Watching","trigger":"Take +1 Cunning (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Blindside"],"startingEquipment":[],"extras":{"background":"One of the background questions on the playbook concerns what happened to the Ronin's former master (their demise, which freed the Ronin)."},"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Harry","Storm a Group","Vicious Strike"]},"startingValue":11,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Scoundrel","blurb":"You are a lucky, dangerous vagabond, acting more as destroyer and troublemaker than anything else, perhaps creating chaos and destruction for its own sake.\n\nDestructive, risky, wild, mischievous. The Scoundrel is a stealthy destroyer, an arsonist, rebel, and agent of chaos in a mask.\n\nAs the Scoundrel, you're a troublemaker, for good and for ill. You can cause a lot of trouble for tyrants and oppressors, but you'll create just as much trouble for your comrades. That's okay, though—your high Luck means you're just about as good as can be expected at getting out of those sticky situations you create.\n\nThe Scoundrel might have a bit of a tendency to be antisocial with the rest of the vagabonds—if they grow too frustrated with the way you blow up situations and use dangerous and extreme solutions, then the other vagabonds might want to part ways with the troublemaker. You should make liberal use of the pleading to get the other PCs to go along with your plans, and you should play hard into your connections—you've got a friend and a partner at least, and those positive relationships should help make up for your mischief!\n\nThat said, when playing a Scoundrel, be sure that you don't create meaningless chaos (at least, not often). Even if you have the Chaos drive, you're actually after a particular goal, not just chaos for its own sake. Play towards your goals, towards accomplishing ends—even if you tend to blow things up along the way, it's more fun if the explosions are purposeful.\n\nYour natures both point at your troublemaking essence. If you're an \"Arsonist,\" then you have incentive to cause more destruction than necessary in accomplishing your ends. If you're \"Combative,\" then you have incentive to start fights you probably can't win. In both cases, you're going to cause a LOT of trouble to get back your exhaustion. The more you can get buy-in from your fellow vagabonds before things explode, the better.\n\nBut when the time comes, don't hesitate to hit your moves and blow stuff up. The Scoundrel is a fun playbook because of the trouble it creates—it's not a playbook for playing it safe, no matter what your pals think!","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":-1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":2,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Arsonist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you use needlessly destructive or damaging methods to solve a problem."},{"name":"Combative","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to start a fight against overwhelming opposition."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."}],"connections":["Friend: ____________ and I once met and pulled off a mad, impossible stunt together. What did we do? Why?","Partner: ____________ and I destroyed a faction's resource, on behalf of an opposing faction. Why?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Explosive Personality","trigger":"When you wreck something with flagrantly dangerous means (explosives, uncontrolled flame, etc.), roll with Luck instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Luck"},{"name":"Create to Destroy","trigger":"When you use available materials to rig up a dangerous device, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you cobble together something that will do what you want, one time.","10+":"On a 10+, choose one.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose two. The device is:","miss":"On a miss, you need some vital component to finish it; the GM will tell you what."},"options":["More dangerous than intended","Larger or more unwieldy than intended","More temperamental and fragile than intended"],"notes":null,"stat":"Finesse"},{"name":"It's a Distraction!","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat to blindside someone while they are distracted by environmental dangers (a raging fire, an oncoming flood, etc.), roll with Luck instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You gain the roguish feat Blindside (it does not count against your limit).","stat":"Luck"},{"name":"Daredevil","trigger":"When you dive into a dangerous situation without forethought or planning, treat yourself as having \"Luck Armor,\" with 1 box of wear (remember, armor is only \"destroyed\" when you would mark another box of wear, and all its boxes are full).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You're at your luckiest when you go into danger without hesitation. The \"Luck Armor\" automatically goes away once the danger has passed, and the next time you would have \"Luck Armor,\" you gain it as if it was brand new with clear boxes."},{"name":"Danger Mask","trigger":"While you have your mask on, any notoriety you gain is doubled, any prestige you gain is halved, and take +1 to trust fate and all Scoundrel playbook moves.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You have a mask or outfit you wear when you go about your most destructive work—more of a calling card, an identifier of \"the real you,\" than a disguise. Treat it as a piece of equipment with two boxes of wear. If your mask is ever taken from you, mark exhaustion. If your mask is ever destroyed, mark 4-exhaustion. If your mask is destroyed, you can make a new mask when time passes."},{"name":"Better Lucky than Good","trigger":"When you use a weapon move (basic or skilled), mark exhaustion to roll with Luck instead of the listed stat.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Luck"}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Sneak","Hide"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Improvise","Quick Shot","Vicious Strike"]},"startingValue":8,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Thief","blurb":"You are a cunning, criminal vagabond, capable of stealing even the most well-guarded treasures, perhaps committed to crime and theft for its own sake.\n\nCrafty, professional, nimble, quiet. The Thief is the ultimate criminal, taking whatever valuables they can grab from any treasure room, vault, or safe, no matter how secure.\n\nAs the Thief, you are likely the single best vagabond in your band with regard to roguish feats. Your high Finesse and your four chosen roguish feats make you more than capable of shoring up any gaps in your band's skill set or solving problems through illicit action. You should be looking for ways to bring your skills to bear and solve problems.\n\nYou're not in trouble when it comes to fights—you are a vagabond, after all—but by default, you'd likely prefer to solve things through stealth and guile. That said, part of the push-pull in the playbook is that your fellow vagabonds aren't going to be able to follow you into every place you sneak. The more you can create opportunities for your fellows to follow by opening doors, leaving ropes out open windows, and so on, the more you can rely on them when a fight (inevitably) breaks out.\n\nYour general skill set is about getting through trouble stealthily, without calling attentions to your activities, so your natures instead push you to cause some problems for yourself. That's great! Embrace the trouble you get into by selfishly stealing things and grievously insulting authority figures.\n\nYour natures—\"Kleptomaniac\" and \"Rebellious\"—are both likely to get you into hot water. \"Selfishly steal something\" always means that you're stealing something you want, and something likely to cause you and yours trouble, instead of stealing something that you and your whole band have agreed is necessary. Similarly, \"grievously insult, defy, or anger\" means that whatever you do, you're pretty much guaranteed the authority figure will react—if you haven't taken enough action that they react, then you haven't hit the trigger.\n\nAt its heart, the Thief is a pretty direct, simple playbook—steal stuff and get away with it!—but you provide real utility to the rest of your band. So pay attention to their goals and desires, too. Much of the time, they'd love to have your help picking locks, sneaking into places, and nabbing vital treasures. You get to show off and help a friend!","stats":{"Charm":0,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":2,"Luck":1,"Might":-1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Kleptomaniac","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to selfishly steal something valuable or important."},{"name":"Rebellious","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you grievously insult, defy, or anger figures of authority."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."}],"connections":["Professional: I stole something important, something needed or craved, for ___________. I proved my worth to them.","Friend: ____________ sprang to get me out of holding, whether they bailed me out or rescued me. I owe them."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Breaking and Entering","trigger":"When you attempt roguish feats to get into or out of a place you've previously been, you can mark exhaustion to make the move as if you had rolled a 10+, instead of rolling.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Disappear Into the Dark","trigger":"When you slip into shadows while unnoticed, mark exhaustion and hold 1.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"As long as you remain quiet, move slowly, and hold 1 for this move, you will remain hidden. If you inadvertently reveal yourself, lose your hold. Spend your hold to reveal yourself from a darkened place, suddenly and without warning. If you attack someone immediately after spending the hold, take +3 on the roll."},{"name":"Rope-a-Dope","trigger":"When you evade and dodge your enemy so as to tire them out, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you can mark exhaustion to make them mark 2-exhaustion.","10+":"On a 10+, you can mark exhaustion to make them mark 3-exhaustion.","miss":"On a miss, they catch you in the middle of a dodge—you're at their mercy."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Finesse"},{"name":"Small Hands","trigger":"When you grapple with an enemy larger than you, roll with Finesse instead of Might.","outcomes":{"miss":"On a miss, they overpower you—you're at their mercy."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Finesse"},{"name":"Master Thief","trigger":"Take +1 Finesse (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Nose for Gold","trigger":"When you figure someone out, you can always ask (even on a miss):","outcomes":null,"options":["what is the most valuable thing they are carrying?"],"notes":"When you read a tense situation, you can always ask (even on a miss):\n· what is the most valuable thing here?"}],"startingRoguishFeats":[],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Improvise","Parry","Trick Shot"]},"startingValue":6,"roguishFeatsChoose":4},{"name":"The Tinker","blurb":"You are an adept, clever vagabond, interested in mechanisms and craftsmanship, perhaps possessed of ideas that separate you from those around you.\n\nGenius, awkward, incautious, inventive. The Tinker is an incredibly capable maker and mechanic, solving problems through devices and clever…well…tinkering.\n\nThe Tinker is more than a crafter or a smith—they’re a true wonder with mechanics, and they’re able to string up all manner of equipment and devices with base supplies. Compared to most clearings’ smiths and crafters, the Tinker is practically a wizard.\n\nBetween the Tinker’s Toolbox and Repair moves, they are oriented more towards longer-term goals and objectives than nearly any other playbook. In practice, that means the Tinker’s projects will often be the spur for the PCs to take action; the Tinker needs the other vagabonds’ help to get the materials they need, or to secure a meeting with the Royal Engineer of the Marquisate, or whatever the case may be.\n\nThe Tinker’s natures point at their potentially strange, “exile-worthy” beliefs in ways that prompt them to action. A “Perfectionist” Tinker can get in trouble when they help the wrong denizens. And a “Radical” Tinker might try to improve minds as well as materials and wind up saying the wrong thing to the wrong crowd, for example suggesting that monarchy might not be the greatest governmental system to a room full of Eyrie nobles.\n\nThe Tinker absolutely needs the other vagabonds in the band to support them. The Tinker is far from incompetent (like all vagabonds), but unlike some other vagabonds the Tinker is no match for a troop of armed soldiers on their own. Fortunately, every other vagabond will love having a Tinker around to repair their equipment and sometimes even arm them anew.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":2,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Perfectionist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you replace someone else’s existing tool or resource with something truly great."},{"name":"Radical","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you espouse dangerous ideas to the wrong audience."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Professional: ____________ and I have been working together well for a while. We read each other’s moves easily.","Family: _____________ and I had each other’s back when we were run out of a clearing because our natures got out of hand."],"playbookMovesChoose":1,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Toolbox","trigger":"When you open up your toolkit and dedicate yourself to making a thing or to getting to the bottom of something, decide what and tell the GM.","outcomes":{"any":"The GM will give you between 1 to 4 conditions you must fulfill to accomplish your goal, including time taken, materials needed, help needed, facilities/tools needed, or the limits on the project. When you accomplish the conditions, you accomplish the goal."},"options":["Feature: assorted scrap wood","Feature: assorted gears and springs","Feature: esoteric hand tools","Feature: manuals","Feature: assorted medicines","Feature: portable alchemy kit","Feature: sewing kit","Feature: cookware","Feature: minor explosives","Drawback: heavy (counts as 2 Load instead of 1)","Drawback: bulky & obvious","Drawback: stolen","Drawback: fragile"],"notes":"You have a kit of tools and supplies with which you work on long-term projects. Choose two features and one drawback from the options."},{"name":"Repair","trigger":"When you repair destroyed personal equipment with your toolbox, the GM will set one condition as per the Toolbox move.","outcomes":{"any":"Fulfill it, and clear all wear for that equipment. When you repair damaged personal equipment with your toolkit, you do it as long as you spend depletion or Value, 1 for 1, for each box of wear you clear."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Big Pockets","trigger":"Take two extra boxes of depletion.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Jury Rig","trigger":"When you create a makeshift device on the fly, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"you create a device that works once, then breaks.","10+":"choose one: It works exceptionally well; You get an additional use out of it","miss":"the device works, but it has an unintended side effect that the GM will reveal when you use it."},"options":["It works exceptionally well","You get an additional use out of it"],"notes":null,"stat":"Cunning"},{"name":"Nimble Mind","trigger":"When you attempt roguish feats involving mechanisms or locks, mark depletion to roll with Cunning instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Dismantle","trigger":"When you dismantle a broken or disabled piece of equipment or machinery, clear 2-depletion.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Disable Device","Pick Lock"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Harry","Improvise","Trick Shot"]},"startingValue":8,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Vagrant","blurb":"You are a charming, survivor vagabond, using words to get out of dangerous situations, perhaps even setting possible predators upon each other to keep them away from yourself.\n\nDeceitful, tricksy, charming, social. The Vagrant is a consummate con artist, a trickster and huckster who gets their way by sweet-talking and lying past trouble.\n\nThe Vagrant is a bit like the Adventurer meets the Thief—a charismatic talker who relies on deception for survival and for gain. They are likely to try to push to the front of the band whenever talking (and especially whenever lying) is involved. As the campaign progresses, however, they might find themself in a tight spot. Their lies generally won't lead to prestige gains with the deceived faction, so at some point, the Vagrant should probably pick one faction they're not going to con left and right…unless, of course, they're okay being on every faction's bad side.\n\nAs with all vagabonds, the Vagrant works best in the \"has a heart of gold\" mode. If the Vagrant has no shame about deceiving anyone and everyone, including innocents and victims of oppressors, then they're going to become unlikable fast. Testing the boundaries of how far the Vagrant will go to land their tricks is part of the character development of the playbook, and a Vagrant player should almost always have some limit to how far they will go.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":-1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Glutton","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you overindulge on vices like drink, food, and gambling."},{"name":"Hustler","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to spring a con on a powerful or dangerous mark."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Family: After ____________ and I pulled off an impressive heist and stole something very valuable from a powerful faction, my bad choices landed me in dire straits. But they bailed me out, and we've been close ever since.","Watcher: ____________ saw through one of my cons, and turned it back on me. How? Why did we forgive each other?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Instigator","trigger":"When you trick an NPC into fighting another NPC, you can remove one option from the 7-9 list—they cannot choose that option instead of doing what you want.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Pleasant Facade","trigger":"When you suck up to or otherwise butter up an unsuspecting NPC, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3. Spend your hold 1 for 1 to deflect their suspicion or aggression away from you onto someone or something else.","7-9":"hold 2. Spend your hold 1 for 1 to deflect their suspicion or aggression away from you onto someone or something else.","miss":"your attempts at flattery are suspicious—they're going to keep their eye on you."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Charm"},{"name":"Desperate Smile","trigger":"When you trust fate to see you through by begging, pleading, or abasing yourself, roll with Charm instead of Luck.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Charm"},{"name":"Charm Offensive","trigger":"When you play upon an enemy's insecurities, concerns, or fears to distract them with words during a fight, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"you create an opening for yourself—make any available weapon move against them at +1, or strike quickly and deal injury to them.","7-9":"you also tick them off; they aren't listening to you anymore, no matter what you do, until the situation drastically changes.","miss":"you infuriate them—they come at you, hard, and you're not prepared."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Cunning"},{"name":"Let's Play","trigger":"When you play a game of skill and wit to loosen another's tongue, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they let slip something useful or valuable.","7-9":"you have to lose the game to get them there; mark depletion.","miss":"they're better than you ever thought; either mark depletion and cut your losses, or mark 3-depletion and they'll start talking."},"options":[],"notes":null,"stat":"Charm"},{"name":"Pocket Sand","trigger":"When you throw something to confuse an opponent's senses at close or intimate range, roll with Cunning instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Take the weapon skill Confuse Senses (it does not count against your limit).","stat":"Cunning"}],"startingRoguishFeats":["Pick Lock","Sleight of Hand"],"startingEquipment":[],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Harry","Improvise","Quick Shot","Vicious Strike"]},"startingValue":9,"roguishFeatsChoose":0},{"name":"The Champion","blurb":"You are a would-be hero and legend, a defender of the innocent and a standard-bearer of lost causes. Yours is the heroic narrative, even if you sometimes oversimplify things.\n\nDriven, noble, righteous, fervent. The Champion is a would-be hero who has chosen a side in the Woodland War, an eager representative of one of the factions…and a scourge and enemy of another.\n\nAs the Champion, you are a capable warrior and dangerous opponent, but you're also a self-proclaimed voice for the ordinary denizens of the Woodland. You're intensely interested in ensuring those who rule the Woodland do right by even the smallest mouse—which means taking a side among the real contenders in the battle for Woodland rule.\n\nThose you consider the Just are your idea of \"the good guys,\" your idea of the faction that can actually deliver a better, united, righteous future for the whole Woodland. The Just can't be the denizens—they aren't a united faction like the Woodland Alliance; they're just the individual dwellers of the myriad clearings, leading independent lives. Remember that you don't want the Woodland to devolve into a bunch of smaller fiefdoms. Someone has to rule the Woodland, right? You know which faction can be trusted to govern justly…and which faction must be opposed with every ounce of strength you have to give to the cause.\n\nThat said, the Enemy doesn't always need to stand as a symbol of all that is terrible. You may oppose them because you find some part of their philosophy to be dangerous, or because a particular leader within the faction can't be trusted. Be aware, though, that the more intense your loathing of the Enemy, the less likely you can change your opposition to them in the future. It's much easier to decide that a disorganized faction has become trustworthy than to accept that the monsters you've fought your whole life are redeemable.\n\nProvided your band can make use of your cause, you'll likely find they are willing to support your demands for justice. But if you don't bother convincing your band that the Just are truly worth supporting—and the Enemy is worth opposing—you may find your vagabond friends are willing to let you fight the good fight alone. You can always change your beliefs—if you find yourself out of sync with your band, maybe it's time to reevaluate whose side you're on! As you learn more about the Woodland, it's pretty likely you'll develop a more nuanced image of justice, after all.\n\nYour two natures, \"Advocate\" and \"Exemplar,\" both point to the work you need to do to build your legacy. The powerful NPC you confront about their mistreatment of the weak can be from any faction, including the one you've labeled as the Just. After all, they above all others should act justly! And if you take on a task for the Just in private, it's totally fine if you're the one that makes it public; the denizens deserve to know of the good work you do.","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":-1,"Finesse":-1,"Luck":1,"Might":2},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Advocate","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you confront a powerful NPC about their mistreatment of the powerless or weak."},{"name":"Exemplar","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly take on a challenging task on behalf of the Just and those they represent."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."}],"playbookMovesChoose":1,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Take Up the Call","stat":null,"trigger":"","outcomes":null,"options":["Luminary: When you persuade an NPC to fight for the Just or resist the charms of the Enemy, roll with Might instead of Charm.","Paladin: When you inflict harm on the Enemy, inflict 1 additional harm; when you suffer harm protecting the Just, suffer 1 fewer harm.","Emissary: When you mark prestige with the Just, mark an additional prestige. When you mark notoriety with the Enemy, mark an additional notoriety."],"notes":"Name two non-denizen factions: declare one to be the best hope for the Woodland (The Just) and the other evil tyrants (The Enemy). Take +1 ongoing to protect members of the Just or harm agents of the Enemy. You may switch which factions you consider to be the Just or the Enemy at the end of any session by clearing all prestige from the faction which no longer inspires you; your reputation with both factions remains the same. The Just:____________________ The Enemy:____________________ Choose a role you often fill as a champion:"},{"name":"Of the People","stat":null,"trigger":"When your band travels along a path at a relaxing pace","outcomes":{"hit":"you encounter friendly faces on the journey who offer food and assistance; your band marks half as much depletion as normal.","7-9":"the characters you meet are in a bit of trouble; they expect you to lend a hand.","miss":"a dangerous foe committed to ending your \"righteousness\" catches you (and your friends) unaware and unprepared."},"options":[],"notes":"roll with +1 instead of -1."},{"name":"Skill Against Skill Alone","stat":null,"trigger":"When you grapple with an enemy and roll a 12+","outcomes":{"any":"you may take their blows to incapacitate them; suffer their full harm to fill their exhaustion or injury track."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"A Just Cause","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you threaten an authority on behalf of the downtrodden","outcomes":{"hit":"the force of your defiance unnerves them; they must make a concession right now to your cause or openly attack you.","10+":"your words are inspirational; you and your allies take a +1 ongoing against them and their allies if they attack you.","miss":"the authority reveals that the cause you champion is not as just as you were led to believe."},"options":[],"notes":"mark notoriety with the authority's faction"},{"name":"Raw Force","stat":null,"trigger":"When you use either weapon skill","outcomes":{"any":"you can mark exhaustion to roll with Might."},"options":[],"notes":"Take one of the following weapon skills: Disarm or Parry (it does not count against your limit)."}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Quick Shot","Storm a Group","Trick Shot"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Sleight of Hand"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":11,"connections":["Protector: ____________ is a true hero, someone whom even I look up to for their moral clarity. What did they do that convinced me of their righteousness?","Family: ____________ and I are more-or-less siblings after years spent in each other's company. Why have we struggled to get along in the past?"]},{"name":"The Chronicler","blurb":"Curious, perceptive, clever, demanding. The Chronicler is a historian of the Woodland, a scribe and scholar dedicated to uncovering and recording the secrets others might prefer to keep hidden.\n\nAs the Chronicler, you have a unique relationship with information. You're good at getting it—searching through documents, reading the room, finding those with the real story—and you know how to put it to use to get things done. Other vagabonds might sharpen their blade before a fight; you know that no strike of the sword is as mighty as a properly placed stroke of the pen.\n\nBut your inquisitive demeanor is likely to get you into trouble—denizens with secrets don't want their business spread around. You may need a fellow vagabond with a sword to keep that pen in good working order. If you're ready to learn the truth (and spread it to the Woodland), make sure to have a few friends on hand to help you keep your head!\n\nYour two natures, \"Observer\" and \"Activist,\" reflect your desire both to get the Woodland's secrets and to use them to make life better for denizens and their communities. \"Observer\" puts you in harm's way, but it doesn't say you have to go alone! \"Activist,\" on the other hand, demands you make a public pronouncement about a \"vital\" change; you have to believe in the value of the change, although fulfilling your nature doesn't require you to present a dissertation on the subject.\n\nYour drives point you towards all sorts of goals you can latch onto as you dig into the Woodland's history. You might take on the causes of the local community, dedicate yourself to exploring the forests, or even champion one of the factions in the Woodland War!","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":2,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Observer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation to try to witness a significant or secret event or meet an important individual."},{"name":"Activist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly confront the leadership of a clearing about changes you think are vital to the community's success."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."}],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"The Worth of a Book","stat":null,"trigger":"When you study your tomes and scrolls to discover old techniques or methods to solve an intractable problem—curing a deadly disease, ending a drought, legally unseating a leader, etc.—decide what you want to accomplish and tell the GM.","outcomes":{"any":"The GM will give you between 1 to 4 conditions you must fulfill to discover a path forward, including time taken, additional information needed, mentors or translators needed, facilities/tools needed, or the limits of your solution. When you fulfill the conditions, you gain whatever knowledge you were seeking—it's up to you to put it to use."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"An Eye for the Real Story","stat":null,"trigger":"When you read a tense situation, mark exhaustion—even on a miss—to spot someone who knows more than they're letting on.","outcomes":{"any":"Take a +1 ongoing to convince them to share their secrets with you when you get them in private."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Search the Records","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you examine the documents, records, or assorted notes of an important NPC (your call), roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"You discover evidence of their secrets; the GM will tell you who would pay for the information you've uncovered.","10+":"You also take a 12+ instead of rolling the next time you try to figure them out.","miss":"Your search yields terrible news—someone is acting against you or your interests in an unexpected arena."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Loremaster","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you consult your knowledge in order to understand a political conflict, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"The GM tells you what information you remember that completes your understanding of the messy situation.","10+":"You can ask a followup question; the GM will answer honestly.","miss":"Something about the situation doesn't fit the history—the GM will tell you what has radically shifted."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Good Advice","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you offer an NPC advice about a sticky situation, offer them the best advice you've got and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"They see the wisdom of your suggestion; they have to mark exhaustion or incorporate your advice into their plans.","7-9":"You let something about your own plans or allegiances slip as you try to help them out.","miss":"The advice angers or offends them; the GM will tell you what local custom you've overstepped with your meddling."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Dedicated Scholar","stat":null,"trigger":"Take an extra box of exhaustion. When you acquire a new tome or scroll documenting the history of the Woodland, clear your exhaustion track.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Improvise","Parry","Trick Shot"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Disable Device","Pickpocket"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":8,"connections":["Partner: _________ and I exposed a dark secret of a faction, leading to a meaningful political change. What was it? And which member of that faction hates us for it?","Peer: I think _________ sees the truth of the world, and I value their perspective deeply. What kinds of information do they see that I often overlook?"]},{"name":"The Envoy","blurb":"Charming, subtle, political, respected. The Envoy is the trusted neutral agent of the Woodland, a political operative and mercenary whose greatest asset is the plausible deniability they offer to the powers that be.\n\nAs the Envoy, you have a light touch for a vagabond—one of the few outcasts who is welcome nearly anywhere you go. Every faction has a use for you! They may wish to employ you to resolve some difficult situation, to deliver a message or threat, or even just to help them understand how best to proceed in a conflict with unfamiliar foes. You are useful to their plans, and they will gladly offer you prestige and coin if you're willing to work on their behalf.\n\nBut you are still a vagabond. The factions of the Woodland find you valuable precisely because you are expendable, and many won't hesitate to turn on you if they feel you've outstayed your welcome. Don't be afraid to use your moves—Turncoat, Trust in Me, Kiss the Ring—to turn on them before they cast you aside, and never forget to use your position and influence to secure the best deal you can from the powers that be. Just be careful not to acquire too much notoriety, lest your status as a diplomat be called into question!\n\nYour natures, \"Agent\" and \"Sworn,\" both involve you working on someone else's behalf. \"Agent\" points you at powerful, influential denizens, those who need a vagabond like you to carry messages and negotiate deals. \"Sworn\" puts the focus on the vulnerable and downtrodden, setting you up as a mediator for those who have no other advocates. The former is perfect if you want to endear yourself to the powers that be; choose the latter if you prefer to instead be a hero to the masses.\n\nYou will often be called upon by the band to negotiate on their behalf too, so lean into those connections and your drives as you act as the negotiator for the other PCs. Remember to plead with other vagabonds to go along with the deals you've struck; sometimes it takes just a little push to get everyone on the same page.","stats":{"Charm":0,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":0,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Agent","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you convince someone influential to allow you to represent their interests."},{"name":"Sworn","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly commit to resolve a dangerous conflict on behalf of someone vulnerable."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."}],"playbookMovesChoose":2,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Diplomat","stat":null,"trigger":"You are known across the Woodland as an accomplished diplomat; you have a track (Diplomat) to reflect your professional reputation, starting at a +1. When you raise your reputation with any faction, raise Diplomat; when you lower your reputation with any faction, lower Diplomat. You cannot lower Diplomat below +0 or raise it above +3.","outcomes":null,"options":["Mark exhaustion to use Diplomat when you ask for a favor or meet someone important for the first time, regardless of the faction of your target.","When you persuade or figure out an important NPC while acting on behalf of another—not you or your band—roll with Diplomat instead of Charm."],"notes":null},{"name":"Fancy Meeting You Here","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you carouse in a popular locale, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"You meet a lackey of a powerful faction in the area—the GM will tell you what they do for the faction, and you tell the GM when and how you met them in the past.","10+":"They get sloppy: they let a secret slip about the faction's plans or offer to introduce you to the faction's leaders on friendly terms.","miss":"Someone who is looking for you finds you first."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Turncoat","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"You gain the roguish feats Blindside and Counterfeit (they do not count against your limit). When you attempt a roguish feat to Blindside someone who trusts you, roll with Cunning instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Plots and Schemes","stat":null,"trigger":"Take +1 Cunning (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Trust in Me","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you soothe or placate an angry NPC, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"You calm their rage.","7-9":"Choose 1.","10+":"Choose 2.","miss":"You can only calm them by redirecting their frustrations."},"options":["They reveal an unexpected vulnerability","They hesitate in their fury; you create an opportunity","They take you further into their confidence"],"notes":null},{"name":"Kiss the Ring","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you exit a meeting with someone rich or powerful, say you took a few of their things and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"The GM tells you what valuable or interesting item you got.","7-9":"It will be missed, but not until you are gone; mark notoriety with that faction.","miss":"They're going to notice; mark 2-notoriety with that faction and either run or come up with a good excuse."},"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":null,"startingRoguishFeats":["Blindside","Counterfeit"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":null,"connections":["Watcher: ____________ reminds me of a powerful political figure of the Woodland. Whom do they resemble? Why is the resemblance so striking to me?","Peer: ____________ and I negotiated a truce between two warring parties within a clearing. Why were they so important to closing the deal?"]},{"name":"The Exile","blurb":"Resilient, fallen, persistent, dangerous. The Exile is a former power player of the Woodland, a once important figure who has been consigned to the life of a vagabond upon banishment from their former faction.\n\nAs the Exile, you have a unique relationship with one of the factions in the Woodland War; everyone in that faction likely knows you and probably has an opinion about you and your fall. Other vagabonds may be able to slip into a clearing without drawing much attention—you tend to make a scene wherever you go!","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":-1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":1,"Might":1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Schemer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you promise valuable resources to a dangerous Woodland figure to secure their aid."},{"name":"Avenger","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly attack those who have wronged you or your sworn vassals and wards."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."}],"playbookMovesChoose":2,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Known by All","stat":null,"trigger":"When you first encounter an important NPC from your former faction, you may declare them to be an old ally—choose and mark one unmarked option from the list below instead of meeting someone important—and roll.","outcomes":{"hit":"Their loyalty has not diminished; they offer whatever aid they can, even risking their own reputation and safety.","7-9":"They can only assist you if they can pretend you forced their hand and cover their tracks when you leave; mark as much notoriety with their faction as you added to your roll.","miss":"Your attempt to reconnect only reveals your desperation; mark as much notoriety as you added to your roll and know that those who hunt you will be here soon."},"options":["They shared your political networks; roll with +1.","You worked closely with them for years; roll with +2.","They were a loyal friend or dutiful servitor; roll with +3."],"notes":"When you have marked all three options, clear them all; your agents will tell you of an opportunity to redeem yourself in the eyes of your faction now that they know you are still active."},{"name":"Above It All","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you trick an NPC into granting you access or information by pretending to be a high-ranking faction leader, roll with Charm instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"I Bring You...","stat":null,"trigger":"When you spend time talking to the denizens of a clearing, mark exhaustion to learn what vital resource or fugitive the powers that be seek.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"When you deliver a vital resource or prisoner to a faction, you may ask for a favor from the faction as if you rolled a 12+ in addition to marking prestige. If your Reputation with that faction is already +2 or greater, you may instead sway the NPC whose cause you most directly benefited with your contribution as if you rolled a 12+."},{"name":"Greatest of the Age","stat":null,"trigger":"When you engage an enemy in melee, you take all four options and one for double effect when you roll a 12+.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Born to Be a King","stat":"Charm","trigger":"Take +1 Charm (max+3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Fancy Paper","stat":null,"trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat to produce counterfeit documents using your intimate knowledge of your home faction's politics and procedures, mark notoriety with that faction to make the move as if you had rolled a 12+.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You gain the roguish feat Counterfeit (it does not count against your limit)."}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Quick Shot","Storm a Group","Vicious Strike"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Sneak"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":11,"connections":["Protector: I see greatness in _________ that I wish to nurture...and perhaps turn to my own purposes. What is it about them that inspires me so?","Family: _________ sheltered me in the earliest days of my exile when I was at my most vulnerable. Why did they offer me such kindness in my moment of need?"]},{"name":"The Heretic","blurb":"Abrasive, outspoken, committed, divergent. The Heretic is a vagabond who has come to adhere to a cause or ideology that has no true home in any clearing or faction, a believer who refuses to compromise on what truly matters.\n\nAs the Heretic, you have a belief system that drives you to action, an internal motivation that pushes you to take risks in order to make the world a better place. You don't have to subscribe to a particularly complex religious or cultural belief system, but you do need to pick at least two fundamental tenets and be clear about how and why they matter to you. Work with the GM to make sure it's understood what other denizens who subscribe to this ideology think as well.\n\nMake sure your band knows what you believe! They will have to live with the consequences of your beliefs nearly as often as you do; you don't want them to be surprised by your ideology. You may be driven by your cause, but as long as you are a PC, you must have a place in the band as well. Find ways through your connections, drives, and other relationships to balance your beliefs against your membership in the band.\n\nYour natures, \"Believer\" and \"Healer,\" are deeply contrasting. \"Believer\" focuses on your enacting the tenets of your cause in the world, calling out authorities who hold opposing beliefs—such confrontations almost always lead to further conflicts. \"Healer,\" in contrast, focuses on resolving conflicts between foes from different factions, relying less on your ideology and more on the general idea that you see the world differently from the rest of the Woodland; you're more open to new ways of resolving old fights, and starting a productive conversation between those foes will activate the nature.\n\nYour drives can help you direct yourself towards your beliefs—several of them line up with the two fundamental tenets of your cause, and picking the ones that match perfectly is a great way to ensure that you are rewarded for adhering to your belief system.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":-1,"Luck":1,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Believer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you publicly call out a symbol or authority dedicated to beliefs opposed to yours."},{"name":"Healer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you attempt to start a dialogue between two foes from different factions."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."}],"playbookMovesChoose":1,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Friends Indeed","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you first seek out those who share your cause after arriving in a clearing, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"You find one or two; they provide what they can in service to your collective work.","7-9":"They also tell you about a threat to your shared ideology that has arisen in the clearing.","miss":"You are caught by someone in the clearing who openly despises your kind."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Hear Me!","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you give an inspiring speech to a persuadable crowd in the service of your cause, mark exhaustion and roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"You sway them; pick 2.","7-9":"You must put yourself at the crowd's mercy and lead them directly for them to follow through.","miss":"The crowd is moved to action but ignores your guidance, leading to terrible consequences."},"options":["They tear down an opposing symbol","They overthrow a vulnerable tyrant","They destroy the trappings of tradition","They elevate someone overlooked","They deliver justice to the wicked"],"notes":null},{"name":"Destroy Something Beautiful","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you wreck a false idol or symbol of oppression alongside your allies, roll with Charm instead of Might; you and all your allies clear an exhaustion, even on a miss.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Devilish Charm","stat":null,"trigger":"When you trick an NPC you've previously aided or impressed, mark exhaustion to make the move as if you had rolled a 12+ instead of rolling.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Center of the Universe","stat":"Charm","trigger":"Take +1 Charm (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"You Shall Not Pass","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you plant yourself in the way of your enemies, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"Your foes cannot get past you until they take you down—brace yourself.","10+":"Choose 1.","7-9":"Choose 2.","miss":"Your enemies find or create a new way past you that makes your situation far worse."},"options":["You suffer +1 harm from all your enemies' attacks","A single enemy (GM's choice) slips past you","You cannot retreat from your position"],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Disarm","Quick Shot","Storm a Group"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Sleight of Hand"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":9,"connections":["Protector: ____________ has come to share my beliefs; I must stand with them, no matter the cost. What happened to us that convinced them of the wisdom of my cause?","Watcher: ____________ was once hurt greatly by someone who shared my cause. Why do I think I might still win them over? What have I already tried to do to earn their trust?"]},{"name":"The Pirate","blurb":"You are a rogue boat captain, at home on the waters of the Woodland's rivers, lakes, or bays, free from the sway of land-bound life and more than willing to do whatever it takes to maintain that freedom. Flamboyant, connected, skillful, chaotic. The Pirate is the captain of a ship, capable of moving cargo and people up and down the rivers of the Woodland, all while finding a little extra time for mischief and adventure! As the Pirate, you're a bit of a paradox: you love chaos and adventure and double crosses and rumors...yet you also have the responsibility of managing your boat and its cargo! The truth is that your position as captain is what makes your chaotic adventures possible—you aren't bound to any home because your true place in the Woodland is on your boat. No one can demand your servitude when you rule the rivers!","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Rogue","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you attempt to doublecross, triplecross, or betray a powerful or dangerous NPC."},{"name":"Merchant","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you carry valuable goods or treasure past danger, difficulty, or blockade."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."}],"playbookMovesChoose":1,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Small Ship","stat":null,"trigger":"By default, your ship has a wear track with four boxes. Mark wear when it suffers serious damage or when a move calls for it. When your ship's wear track is filled, it is dead in the water and must be repaired at port. If you must mark wear on your ship but its whole track is full, your ship is lost. If you ever lose the ship the GM may present you with an opportunity to get a new one.","outcomes":null,"options":["Blessing — stocked: your ship gains a 2-box depletion track of cargo and gear","Blessing — nimble: take +1 ongoing to tricking NPCs when relying on your ship's speed","Blessing — renowned: take +1 to Reputation with a chosen faction while on your ship","Blessing — swift: once per session, mark wear to outrun any pursuer on the water","Flaw — dreaded: take -1 to Reputation with a chosen faction while on your ship","Flaw — rickety: your ship has one fewer box of wear than usual","Flaw — clumsy: take -1 ongoing to trusting fate when piloting your ship carefully","Flaw — stolen: someone dangerous is pursuing you to recover their property"],"notes":"Your Ship's Name: _____________________ Wear. Choose 2 Blessings and choose 2 Flaws."},{"name":"Sail On","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you travel from clearing to clearing by ship, mark wear on the ship and roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"you reach the next port; the GM will tell you one (mostly) friendly denizen you know there.","7-9":"they are holding a grudge—work it out or offer at least 2-Value to let things go.","miss":"you are caught in a dangerous situation along your route before you arrive at port."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Swashbuckler","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you first charge into battle by swinging, diving, or leaping to engage an enemy in melee at close range, roll with Luck instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Eye for Treasure","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you ask around a port about valuable trade, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"you learn of nearby cargo worth your time.","10+":"you know exactly where the cargo is held or how to intercept the shipment.","miss":"you hear only of well-guarded or difficult-to-reach cargo...and your questions start drawing attention."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Plenty of Rum","stat":null,"trigger":"Once per session, you may plead with a vagabond a second time in a session by sharing your rum (mark depletion) with the target of your pleading.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Sea Legs","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat aboard a ship to Blindside, Sneak, Hide, or perform Acrobatics, roll with Luck instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Parry","Storm a Group","Trick Shot","Vicious Strike"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Blindside","Pick Lock"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":8,"connections":["Partner: __________ and I seized valuable cargo from a faction together. Who did we rob? Why?","Family: __________ had a good relationship with my former captain. How have they supported me in taking on the role as my own?"]},{"name":"The Prince","blurb":"Precocious, scrappy, savvy, inheritor. The Prince is a scion of a vagabond family, a second-generation rogue who has come into their own in the shadow of their parent's legacy, acquiring their skills, their tools…and their old allies and enemies.\n\nThe Prince is a younger character—not a child per se, but also not a denizen whose own adventures and accomplishments have eclipsed their parents' legacy. They are a skilled and competent vagabond! After all, they've been raised from birth to be an outlaw!\n\nAs the Prince, your Heirloom Weapon is a huge part of your character—take the time to design something that excites you and give it a cool story! Maybe that's a reliable crossbow with flexible skills your parents stole from an Eyrie weaponsmith or a deadly sword with a feared reputation they forged themselves long before the Marquisate came to the Woodland.\n\nYour natures point to your past or your future. \"Scion\" activates when you engage old conflicts, protecting those who were allied with your parents and attacking old enemies. \"Trailblazer,\" on the other hand, activates when you join, follow, or lead a group in some new, risky, and exciting direction. It doesn't have to be a literal new path—a new plan or new idea is good enough—but you have to be pursuing a new way of doing things, a new approach, a new direction, any of which comes with its own array of unknowns and new surprises.\n\nEither way, get used to the idea that many denizens of the Woodland already think they know you. Your drives give you some goals you may choose to focus on, but you'll find no shortage of NPCs in the Woodland who think they already know what side you should be on based on how your parents handled things.\n\nYou are a second-generation vagabond, heir to your parents' masteries and knowledge, but also born to this life of roguery and independence—you are not a vagabond by your own volition.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":1,"Luck":1,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Scion","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter danger to attack the enemies or defend the allies of your parents."},{"name":"Trailblazer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you depart on a wild and risky new course of action with others."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"playbookMovesChoose":1,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Heirloom Weapon","stat":null,"trigger":"Your parents bestowed a family heirloom upon you—it has 4 boxes of wear, and whatever its Value, it is priceless to you. If the weapon is ever destroyed, the GM will tell you what tasks you must undertake to restore it.","outcomes":null,"options":["Choose a weapon type: dagger, axe, hammer, sword, spear, crossbow, bow","Choose an appropriate range: intimate, close, far","Reliable: +2 boxes of wear and an additional range.","Feared: When you engage in combat against foes who recognize this weapon, inflict morale harm on them.","Deadly: When you inflict harm with this weapon, inflict +1 harm.","Double-Headed: One edge inflicts injury, the other exhaustion. Declare which side you are using at the start of a fight.","Flexible: Choose 2 weapon skill tags for this weapon.","Unique: Your weapon is of unusual design; once per session, mark exhaustion to ignore the harm inflicted on you by a single attack.","Rousing: After you successfully inflict injury on a dangerous enemy, mark wear to clear exhaustion from every ally who saw you land the blow."],"notes":"Choose two features."},{"name":"Legacy","stat":null,"trigger":"When you meet someone important for the first time, mark your legacy track to take a 10+ instead of rolling. When your legacy track is full, tell the GM, clear the track, and roll. Take +1 for each \"yes\" to the following questions:","outcomes":{"hit":"Someone with unfinished business with your parents finds you.","10+":"They arrive without warning.","miss":"An ordinary denizen warns you about someone who might seek you out; mark your legacy track."},"options":["Are you in a clearing?","Is anyone looking for you?","Do you have +2 or -2 Reputation with at least one faction?"],"notes":null},{"name":"One of Us","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you try to figure out or persuade vagabonds, bandits, revolutionaries, or outcasts, roll with Luck instead of Charm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Tall Tales","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you attempt to impress a crowd with a wild story, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"The crowd is moved; everyone in your band takes +1 ongoing to persuade or trick someone in line with the story.","10+":"Someone foolish even approaches you with profitable work!","miss":"Your stories attract someone in desperate need of help you're not equipped to give."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"No Jail Can Hold Me","stat":null,"trigger":"Take the roguish feat Pick Lock (it does not count against your limit). When you attempt to escape confinement, mark exhaustion to shift a miss to a 7-9.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Favored","stat":null,"trigger":"Take +1 Luck (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Disarm","Harry","Parry"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Hide","Sneak"],"roguishFeatsChoose":2,"startingValue":7,"connections":["Peer: __________ used to work with one of my parents and invited me to join the band when I came of age. How did I impress them with my talents?","Family: __________ was mentored by one of my parents. What vagabond skills did they learn from my parents that I've always struggled to master?"]},{"name":"The Raconteur","blurb":"Dashing, adroit, distracting, audacious. The Raconteur is a performer and a storyteller, a vagabond who shapes the future of the Woodland with a song or story. The Raconteur is a lover, not a fighter. They would far rather sing a song than swing a sword! That doesn't mean the Raconteur is a pushover; they can fight like any other vagabond and also shape public opinion, their performances impacting how the denizens think about the events of the Woodland. You are a storyteller, making coin and earning trust by moving amid the clearings and weaving tales that ultimately teach the denizens what you want them to believe about the Woodland's goings-on.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":1,"Luck":-1,"Might":-1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Legend","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put on a performace in front of a large, attentive audience."},{"name":"Companion","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you effusively praise a friend to a powerful person or group."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."}],"playbookMovesChoose":2,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Tools of the Trade","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you first put on an earnest, public performance in a clearing","outcomes":{"hit":"name a faction you flatter; an important member comes forward to offer you work.","10+":"mark prestige with their faction as well.","miss":"you draw the worst kind of attention to you and your friends."},"options":["Choose a type: musical instrument, poetry book, unique costume, stage prop","Choose a look: battered, fancy, delicate, stained, pristine","Sturdy: +2 boxes of wear; when you tend to your symbol after a public performance, clear a box of wear.","Enchanting: Mark wear instead of exhaustion to add +2 when you help another vagabond by distracting someone with your performance.","Versatile: Choose two equipment tags for your symbol.","Revealing: When you perform in public, mark wear to ask any one character who watched \"what truly motivates your character?\"; take +1 when acting on the answer.","Pleasant: When you perform for your band while traveling along the path, mark wear to clear up to 2 additional exhaustion from each vagabond."],"notes":"You have a valued (at least to you) symbol of your skill and talent; it starts with 3 boxes of wear and whatever its Value, it is essentially priceless to you. Choose three features."},{"name":"Adoring Fans","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you first enter a clearing","outcomes":{"hit":"a fan recognizes you; they relate gossip, offer a place to stay, and show your band around.","10+":"your fan will go even further to help you.","miss":"you meet a fan with good intentions who immediately makes your situation much, much worse."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"All Eyes on Me","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you create a distraction through outlandish performance, mark exhaustion","outcomes":{"hit":"the room can't look away; your allies take +1 ongoing to Sneak, Hide, Pickpocket, or trust fate while you perform.","10+":"hold 1; spend the hold to grant an ally a +3 for one of the aforementioned rolls instead.","miss":"your audience finds something about your performance insulting or misguided; they fall over themselves to give you their opinion."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Quick Fingers, Quicker Eyes","stat":null,"trigger":"When you read a tense situation while performing","outcomes":{"any":"you may always ask one question, even on a miss."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Silver Tongue","stat":null,"trigger":"When you persuade an NPC with a colorful anecdote","outcomes":{"hit":"mark exhaustion on a hit to make them reveal something important and relevant about the situation."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Sweet as Honey","stat":null,"trigger":"Take +1 Charm (max +3).","outcomes":{"any":"Take +1 Charm (max +3)."},"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Disarm","Improvise","Vicious Strike"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Pickpocket","Pick Lock"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":8,"connections":["Friend: __________ and I still talk about the time we were run out of a clearing, even though we thought our adventures would lead the powers that be to treat us as heroes. What did we do? How did it go wrong?","Family: ___________ and I have been through battles, ruin-delves, heists, and more together. Which particular incident made us close? How did I make it famous?"]},{"name":"The Raider","blurb":"Rough, pragmatic, threatening, dangerous. The Raider is a bandit of the Woodland, a brigand who takes what they want by the sword, forgoing stealth and guile in favor of raw force.\n\nThe Raider is an aggressive fighter. They are as strong as some of the other martial vagabonds—the Arbiter, the Ronin, the Champion—and they have moves like Plan of Attack and Fearsome Visage that allow them to set the conflict on their terms, leaving even the strongest forces vulnerable and exposed. Woe to any opposition that underestimates how much damage the Raider and their allies can do!\n\nAs the Raider, you can strike some heavy blows against even the most dangerous opposition, but you've got to decide whose side you're on. Do you want to forge an alliance with a faction that pays well and stays out of your way? Or do you want to keep things even, seeking a balance with all the factions of the Woodland War in the hopes they worry about bigger problems? Do you fight for someone else or yourself?\n\nYour natures, \"Bandit\" and \"Hero,\" give you the option of affirming what others think of you or attempting to rise above your baser instincts in the service of others. \"Bandit\" rewards you for attempting to seize valuables from real, dangerous opposition—a whole unit of Marquisate soldiers, for example—while \"Hero\" incentivizes you to take the side of the vulnerable. The latter may still turn a profit if the dangerous or villainous NPCs have valuables for you to seize, but it's not guaranteed! Either way, you don't have to win either fight to activate your nature; clear your exhaustion when you make the attempt!\n\nThat said, the Raider tends to come across as a villain themselves, even when they mostly target the powerful and cruel. Look to your connections and drives to find reasons to restrain your violence productively and work with your band to accomplish objectives greater than mere banditry. After all, there will be plenty of loot along the way!","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":2,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Bandit","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to use the threat of force to secure valuables from formidable opposition."},{"name":"Hero","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you outright attack a dangerous, oppressive, or villainous NPC."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."}],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Eye For Battle","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you read a tense situation just as violence breaks out, roll with Might instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Ironhide","stat":null,"trigger":"When a group inflicts harm on you, suffer 2 fewer harm from each attack (minimum 1-harm); when you inflict harm on a group, inflict 1 additional harm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Loot and Plunder","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you loot a rich area for valuables, roll with Finesse. On a hit, something out of the ordinary catches your eye; claim it and it's yours.","outcomes":{"10+":"all 3.","7-9":"choose 1:","miss":"you can get your hands on it, but it is sought by dangerous denizens who are all too willing to kill to take it from whoever possesses it."},"options":["It is worth a lot of money (+2-Value)","It is of special value to a particular faction (+4 prestige if traded to them)","It is extremely durable (+1-wear)"],"notes":null},{"name":"Merciful Might","stat":null,"trigger":"When you try to befriend an NPC you've saved from the wrath of another, spend time helping them further (mark exhaustion) or buy them a drink (mark depletion). Your continued kindness pays dividends; they'll share a valuable secret or grant you a serious favor.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Plan of Attack","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you work out a plan of attack with someone, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3.","7-9":"hold 2. You can spend your hold 1-for-1, regardless of distance, while the plan is being carried out to:","miss":"hold 1, but your plan encounters some disastrous opposition right from the start."},"options":["Lend a hand; add +1 to someone's roll (choose after rolling)","Soften a blow; reduce by one the harm someone suffers from a single attack","Ensure your gear holds; allow someone to ignore marking depletion or wear"],"notes":null},{"name":"Fearsome Visage","stat":null,"trigger":"You can make a pointed threat or publicly draw attention to yourself as an enemy of a faction when you have a Reputation of 0 or lower with that faction, not just the usual -3 or -2 reputation required. Remember, you roll as if your negative reputation was positive, so a -1 Reputation becomes a +1 for the roll and a 0 remains a 0.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Cleave","Confuse Senses","Storm a Group","Vicious Strike"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Blindside"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":9,"connections":["Protector: The first time I saw ____________ they piqued my curiosity; I went out of my way to protect them from the ire of my own band. What about them sparked my loyalty?","Watcher: ____________ bested me in combat when I got out of hand. How? Why did I thank them for it?"]},{"name":"The Seeker","blurb":"You are an explorer by nature, interested in free-ranging discovery, delving into ruins, and uncovering whatever secret wonders and ancient truths lie hidden amid the Woodland.\n\nObsessed, prepared, experienced, perceptive. The Seeker is an expert on the ruins and mysteries of the forest, an excavator of old treasures and forbidden places who seeks riches and answers in equal measure.\n\nAs the Seeker, you've got a bunch of useful skills for getting into difficult places, whether you're gaining entrance to an ancient Eyrie ruin or breaking into a vault in a Marquisate-controlled clearing. You're also pretty good at trusting fate to see you through difficult times! Some may see you as nothing more than a glorified tourist, but you're a vagabond through and through, capable of the same amount of trouble as any other outlaw!\n\nThat said, your focus is always going to be the ruins and mysteries of the forest. One of your natures—\"Explorer\"—points directly at the ruins, and Word on the Street allows you to hear of nearby sites when you get some time to talk to the locals. Most of your other moves also give you unique abilities inside and around ruins, and you can usually create all manner of profitable opportunities for your band. But your other nature—\"Historian\"—points to a deeper truth: you seek knowledge and answers about the Woodland, the truth behind the ruins and mysteries of the forest. You know that there are secrets hidden everywhere, both in the ruins and in the clearings, that must be exposed. You and your band are some of the only denizens that can stand up to those who would cover up or obscure the truth!\n\nYour drives are all designed to help further point at the reasons why you seek answers—is it greed? Is it curiosity? Is it just a general desire to see and do new things? Pick the drives that most satisfy your reasons for delving into ruins and other places you shouldn't go.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":1,"Luck":1,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Explorer","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a ruin or other dangerous area of the forest."},{"name":"Historian","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you refuse to allow someone to cover up or obscure the truth."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"playbookMovesChoose":2,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Word on the Street","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you spend time in a clearing talking with locals, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"you catch wind of a nearby unexplored wonder or ruin; someone promises to take you to it for a fair fee (1-Value).","7-9":"the dangers make their price steeper—an additional 1-Value of coin or gear.","miss":"the location is under threat—soon it will be plundered, destroyed, or claimed by another power."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Never Lost","stat":null,"trigger":"Take two additional boxes of injury and depletion you can mark when you confront dangers within a ruin and a +1 ongoing to trusting fate and performing roguish feats while exploring such ancient locales.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Treasurer Hunter","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you sell the treasures you found in a ruin at market, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"you find some buyers.","7-9":"take 1.","10+":"both:","miss":"you still sell the items for a fair price, but someone powerful takes offense at your plunder of such sacred sites."},"options":["You get a good price; you get double what such findings are usually worth","You are popular; mark two prestige with the controlling faction"],"notes":null},{"name":"Adventurer Contract","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you try to convince a powerful NPC to supply an exploratory adventure, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"they give you 8-Value in resources and depletion—but you must fulfill a request.","10+":"they ask for something general—more riches, information, a prize or trophy.","7-9":"they want something specific—a singular treasure, secret knowledge, a lost ritual.","miss":"they mount a competing expedition based on what you have told them."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Watch the Signs","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you first attune yourself to a ruin or mysterious site by taking in its signs, symbols, particular traits, and layout, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3.","7-9":"hold 2.","miss":"you may mark exhaustion to hold 1."},"options":["Identify the quickest path to the closest valuable treasure or knowledge","Disarm a trap or overcome a natural hazard without cost","Name a character within reach about to suffer harm; you suffer it instead","Name a character in the ruin; you cross the distance to them instantly","Take cover in the ruin; ignore all harm from a single attack or catastrophe"],"notes":"While within that ruin or mysterious site, you can spend your hold 1-for-1 to:"},{"name":"Unstable Ground","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you use a rough or chaotic environment—slippery rocks, a crowded market, etc.—to gain an advantage over your opponents in a fight, you can grapple with them using Finesse instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"weaponSkills":{"choose":1,"options":["Confuse Senses","Disarm","Parry","Trick Shot"]},"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Disable Device","Pick Lock"],"roguishFeatsChoose":0,"startingValue":8,"connections":["Partner: ____________ and I have seen the wonders of the Woodland together. What makes them a stalwart companion on my travels?","Peer: ____________ is famous for a discovery of their own. I greatly respect them! What did they discover? How?"]}],"notes":{"connectionTypes":"Connection prompts on each playbook use types such as Partner, Friend, Protector, Professional, Watcher, Family (full list on p.51 per advancement text).","weaponSkillsVsMoves":"A vagabond's weapon skill tags (from weapons/playbook) unlock the corresponding Weapon-category moves. Starting weapon skills are listed per playbook; max 7 total via advancement (not counting playbook-granted skills)."}};
